274	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 09:16:14.16056	--- 6 - Minerals in Human Health.pdf ---\nMinerals in Human\nHealth\nDr. ThilankaRanathunga\nFundamentalsof HumanNutrition\nLearningobjectives\n•Identify the classes of minerals\n•Describe the functions of minerals in human body\n•List the food sources of each mineral\n•List the deficiency symptoms of each mineral\nClassificationofminerals\nTwo classes\n1.Macrominerals – required in large quantities compared to other\nminerals (mg level)\nEx : Calcium, phosphorus, magnesium, sodium, potassium and chloride\n2.Microminerals /trace minerals – required in small quantity (µg\nlevel)\nEx : Iron, zinc, iodine, fluoride, selenium and copper\n•Both macro and micro minerals are essential for the body functions\nCalcium(Ca)\n•The skeleton contains about 99% of the body’s calcium, approximately 1kg of\ncalcium in adult bones\n•The major constituents of bone are Ca and phosphate forming\nhydroxyapatite, which is associated within a mesh of collagen fibers to form a\nrigid structure.\n•The body’s requirement for Ca fluctuates with the rate of bone development\n•Ca is continuously withdrawn and deposited in bones to support physiological\nrequirement of the body\nBone development with age\nFunctionsofcalciuminthebody\n1.Formationofboneandteeth\n•Osteoblasts cells are involved in bone formation\n•Osteoclast cells are involved in bone resorption\n2.Nerveconduction\n•Stimulate exocytosis of synaptic vessels containing Acetyle Cholin\ninto synaptic cleft\n•Ca triggers the release of Acetyle Cholin from the vesicles to synaptic\ncleft\n3.Musclecontraction\n•Calcium interacts with Troponin C to trigger muscle contraction\n•Calcium activates ATP ase\n•Interaction between actin and myosin facilitate excitation and\ncontraction of the muscle\n4.Bloodcoagulation\n•Thrombine should react with fibrinogen to form a clot.\n•Prothrombin is the precursor for thrombin\n•This precursor (Prothrombin) converts to thrombine with the help of\nCa\nCadeficiency\nRickets\n•Disease of children in which bones softened\nand deformed.\n•Bowed legs\nOsteomalacia\n•Among adults\n•Demineralization and softening of bones.\n\nOsteoporosis\n•Bone density become lower than expected level for the particular\nage.\n•Loss of bone material, especially calcium, leading to brittle bones\nFoodsourcesofcalcium\n•Milk and milk products\n•Small fish\n•Meat\n•Nuts\n•Some vegetables\n•Tofu\n•It is an intracellular anion (PO 43-)\n•80% of P in the body is present in the skeletal\n•Rest of the P is available in the cellsPhosphorous(P)\nFunctionsofP\n1. Components in phospholipids, nucleic acids, proteins (casin), enzymes\n2. Formation of bones & teeth\nHydroxyapatite\n3. Central role in energy production – ATP, ADP, PCr\nPhosphocreatine\nATP\nFunctionsofPcont…\n4. Constituents on cell membrane\n5. Buffering agent\n6. Component in 2,3 Diphosphoglyceric Acid (2,3 DPG) : facilitate\noxygen transport\n\nFoodSources\nPhosphorusdeficiency\n•Loss of appetite\n•Anxiety\n•Fragile bones\n•Stiff joints\n•Irregular breathing\n•Numbness\n•Weakness and weight change\n\nSodium\n•Present in the body as a free ions that binds weakly to organic\nmolecule (Na+ .... NaCl)\n•Main electrolyte in the intracellular and extracellular\ncompartments\n•The high amount is present in extracellular fluid\nFunctionsofsodium\n\nMaintainingcidbasebalance\n\nMaintainosmaticpressure\n21\nMuscle and nerve functions\n22\nCellmembranepermeability\nGlucose,galactoseandAAabsorption\nMaintainhearthbeat\nExplainhowexcesssaltintakecancause\nhighbloodpressure.\n26\nFoodSources\nMicro-minerals\n28\nIron(Fe)\n•Fe available as following two forms in foods\n-Hemeiron : in meat, fish and poultry, and is easily absorbed\nto the body (Fe2+)\n-Non-hemeiron : in plant-based foods such as beans, lentils,\nnuts and seeds, whole grains and some vegetables (Fe3+)\n29\nFunctionsofiron\n•Carry O 2: As hemoglobin\n30\n\nFunctionsofironcont…\n•Store O2 : as myoglobin\n•AA production : act as cofactor\n•Collagen production\n•Hormone production\n•Facilitate the functions of\nneurotransmitters\n•Energy production – Cytocrome\n•Act as coenzymes\n31\n\nFactorsaffectingFeabsorption\n•10 – 15% of Fe in the diet will absorb\n•Animal or plant sources (heme or non heme Fe)\n-Heme–inanimal,highlyabsorbable\n-Nonheme–plant,lessabsorbable\n•Fe status of the body\n•Availability of absorption enhancing factors and inhibition\nfactors\n-Enhancingfactors–vitC,cysteine,alcohol,\n-Inhibiting–phyticacid,Phosphorus,dietaryfibers,caffeine,\nCa,EDTA\n•Sex & stage of the life\n32\nFedeficiencysigns\n33\nSigns and symptoms of iron deficiency\n•Pale color palm\n•Pale color eye lid\n•Brittle nails\n•Sleepiness\n34\nIrondeficiency diseases:Irondeficiencyanemia\nNormal hemoglobin levels :\n•13g/100 ml blood for men\n•12g/100 ml blood for women\nAbnormal levels :\n•<6g/100 ml blood -> anaemia\n(classical symptoms)\n•<7g/100 ml blood -> increase in blood pressure\nBUT9.5 g/100 g classified as anaemic\n35\nFoodsources\n36\n\nZinc(Zn)\n•Necessary for about 100 enzymes for chemical reactions\n•It is a major player in the\n- formation of DNA\n- growth of cells\n- Synthesis of proteins\n- healing damaged tissue\n- supporting a healthy immune system\n37\nFunctionsofZinc\n•Act as a cofactor\n•Precursor for insulin formation\n•Maintain gut and skin health\n•DNA / RNA synthesis\n•Involve in energy metabolism\n•Other functions :\n•vitamin A metabolism\n•wound healing\n•immune function\n•taste receptor function\n•fatty acid metabolism\n38\n\nFoodsourcesforzinc\n•Beef 5.9\n•Chicken (dark meat) 3.1\n•Chicken (light meat) 1.0\n•Wholemeal flour 3.0\n•White flour 0.9\n•Oysters 70\n39\nZndeficiency\n•Acute :\n•Anorexia\n•Cessation of growth\n•Skin lesions\n•Diarrhoea\n•Loss of appetite\n•Birth defect\n•Mental effects\n•Hair loss\n•Abnormal taste and smell\n•Chronic :\n•Stunted growth, lack of sexual development, anaemia\n40\nIodine(I)\n•Iodine is found in ionic form (iodide, I-) in foods\n•15 – 50 mg of Iodide is available in human body\n•80% of it is in thyroid glands and rest is in blood\n41\nFunctionsof iodine\n• Formationof thyroidhormones–growthand\ndevelopment\n• Regulatemetabolicrate\n• Development of neuronsinfetus\n• Maintainnormalreproductivefunctions\n• Nutrient digestionandabsorption\n\nIodine deficiency\n• Adults: Goiter, Hypothyroidism, myxeodema(severe\nhypothyroidism)\n- coughing\n- tight feelinginthroat\n-changesinvoice.\n-difficultyswallowing(dysphagia)\n-difficultybreathing\nIodinedeficiencycont…\n• Fetus: Abortions, stillbirths, cognitionabnormalities,\n• Neonate : Cretinism–severementaldefects, stunted\ngrowth, lowfunctionsof bodyorgans\nIodinedeficiencysymptoms\n• Weight gain, fatigueandweakness\n• Feelingcolderthanusual\n• Slowheart rate\n• Learningandmemorydifficulties\n\nFoodsources\n• Seafoods\n• Iodinatedsalt andsalt addedfoods\n• Eggs\n• Milk\n• Plant sources: Dependonthelevelof iodineinsoil\n-Iodineislight sensitive: needtostoreindarkbottles\nRDA\n• Adultsmales: 120µg/day\n• Adult females: 110µg/day\n• Lactating/pregnant mother: 250µg/day
275	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 09:17:24.295404	--- 7 - Nutrition for life cycle.pdf ---\nNutrition through the life cycle \nDr. Thilanka Ranathunga\nFundamentals of Human Nutrition \n\nLearning objectives\n•Describe nutritional requirements for different \nstages of life cycle\n•List critical nutrients in high demand at each \nstage of life \n•Describe the importance of each nutrient for \neach life stage \nNutrition during infancy\n\nSpecial features of infancy\n•Less than 1 year\n•Birth weight doubled by 6 months, tripled by 1st\nyear \n•Growth charts are used to monitor the growth\n•Poor immunity \n•Body systems may not fully developed\n\nCritical nutrients for infants\n•Iron \n•Zn\n•Proteins\n•Vitamin D & calcium\n•EFA\n\nInfant feeding\n•Exclusive breast feeding should be done up to 6 \nmonths\n•No even water should be given up to 6 months\n•Initial milk is very important as it contain  \nCholestrum : improve the immunity \n\nComplementary feeding\n•Food should be given after 6 months\n•Should be rich in iron \n•Rice and cereals with fats at first  as semi solid \nform\n•Pulses, nuts, sprats, fish, green leaves, \npotatoes/sweet potatoes, vegetables –should be \nadded later to the rice mixture\n•Eggs, meat like foods can be incorporated \nthereafter\n•Do not use salt and sugar until one year\nComplementary feeds cont..\n•Introduce foods one by one, after baby adopted \nto new foods\n•Fruits can be given as paste\n•Use cups and spoons to feed\n\n•Breast feeding should be continued and can \nbe done up to 2 years\n•Use motor skills when introduce foods\n•Toasted bread, low sugar biscuits and be \ngiven to eat by themselves with a proper care\n\nComplementary feeds cont..\n•Pay attention on chocking\n•Prepare very hygienically\n•Introduce family foods at the age of 1 year \n•Avoid force feeding\n\nNutrition \nduring \npreschool \nyears\n\nIntroduction \n•1 –4 year period ( 1 –3 year toddlers) \n•Slow growth\nWhy nutrition is important?\n1.Development of feeding skills\n2.Develop food habits that last for whole life \n3.Rapid growth\n4.Low appetite\n5.Prevent nutritional deficiencies\n\nKey nutrients \n•Oils and fat : EPA, DHA  to support brain \ndevelopment\n•30-40 % of energy from fat\n•Protein\n•Zn\n•Ca\n•Fe\n\nCommon feeding problems at preschool age \n•Refuse foods\n•Interest on playing\n•Eat more sweet foods\n•Choking\n•Less vegetables and fruits\n•Infectious diseases\n•Imitating -TV advertisement\n\nFeeding strategies\n•Allow self feeding \n•Keep their own table,  spoons, plates with nice \ncolors shapes \n\n•Small portion sizes\n\n•No snacks/sweeten  beverages before \nmeals (may be 1 –1 ½ hrs)\n\n•Allow them to select and prepare foods or planting \n\n•Allow them to select the time and amount of \nfoods\n\n•Give single foods than mixed food\n•Attractive colors and shape\n•Small frequent meals \n\n•Allow to eat with peers and parents\n\n•Some sweet foods are acceptable \n\nNutrition for adolescents \n\nIntroduction \n•10 –19 years\n•Transitional stage from childhood to adulthood\n•Rapid growth and maturation             \n•Leading to puberty\n•Physiological and psychological changes to \nattain adult capacity \n\nCharacteristics\n•Go through “growth spurt”               last for 2 –3 \nyears\n•Time of growth spurt earlier in girls than boys\n\nNutritional requirements \n•Nutritional requirement is very high because \nof rapid growth\n•Recommendation for nutrients are differ \nperson to person\n•Due to the different stages of sexual \ndevelopment\n•Sexual maturation differed according to the  \nage, body composition and physiological \ndevelopment\nCritical Nutrients\n•Ca–rapid bone development\n•Fe –for all tissue development \n•Zn –for the activity of enzymes\n•Proteins –muscle mass development \n•Folic acids –prepare for pregnancy \n•Low level of P \nNutrition for adults \n\nIntroduction \n•21 –65 years\n•No important nutritional requirements\n•Growth has finished\n•Unhealthy behaviors that developed earlier  \nshow its consequences at this stage\n•Over nutrition is the main problem\n•Physical activities are low\n\nNutritional requirements \n•Vitamin and mineral –essentially similar at age 19 \nand 60 years\n•Micro nutrient dense foods should be taken\n•Low energy dense foods\n•Low fats and sugar\n\nDiseases associated with unhealthy \nlifestyle and nutrition occurred in adults\n•Obesity\n•Diabetes \n•CVD\n•Cancers\n\nWhat are the treatments?\n•Monitoring of blood glucose and screening\n•Changes in diet patterns\n•Increase physical activity \n•Weight loss\n•More fruits and vegetables\n\nNutrition for elderly \n•Age > 65 years\n•Very low nutrient and energy requirements\n•Muscle wasting\n•Loss of teeth and taste sensation \n•Digestive problems\n•Psychological problems  \n\nCritical nutrients and non nutrients  \n•Vitamin D –poor synthesis in skin \n•Calcium –bone desorption is high \n•B12 –low absorption due to low intrinsic \nfactor\n•Antioxidant nutrients \n•Water –poor feeling of thirst \n•Fiber –prevent constipation \nDiets for older adults \n•Semi solid foods\n•Nutrient dense\n•Low in salt and sugar\n•Add fruits and vegetables \n•B12, D, Casupplements\n•Low refined foods  \n\nNutrition during pregnancy \nOne of most dynamic stages of a women life\n•Normal pregnancy 38-42 weeks gestation\n•Split into three trimesters\n1sttrimester 0-13 weeks  \n2nd trimester 13-26 weeks  \n3rd trimester 26-40weeks\n\nRecommnded weight gain during\npregnancy\nBMI before\npreganancy (kg/m2)Recommended\nWeight Gain\nUnderweight, <18.5 28-40 lb (12.5 –18\nkg)\nNormal weight, 18.5-\n24.925-35 lb (11.5 -16kg)\nOverweight, 25-29.9 15-25 lb (7.0-11.5 kg)\nObese, 30 or higher 11-20 lb (5-9.0kg)\nTwin pregnancy 25-54 lb (11.4 -24.5\nkg)\nNutrient needs during pregnancy\n•Nutrient needs vary during the course of the\npregnancy\n•Balanced diet with all food groups are important\n•Key nutrients;\n-Protein\n-Folate\n-Iron\n-Zinc\n-Calcium\n-Some vitamins toxic at high doses\n\nEnergy requirements inpregnancy\n•Should not eat for two persons\n•~300 additional kcal/d ay needed\n• +350/d ay-2nd trimester \n•+450/d -3rdtrimester\n•Assessment of caloric intake is important\n•Most easily assessed by pregnancy weight gain\n•To support metabolic demands and  fetal development\nNutrient needs during lactation\n\n•Weight lost is common : 0.8 kg/month\n•Energy spent for milk production is 500 kcal per \nday in the first 6  months and 400 kcal \nafterward.\n•Maternal fat stores : nutrients to the breast milk\n•Alternative diets : supplements, special \nproducts, some plant based traditional food \nitems Nutrient needs during lactation\nKey nutrients \n•Folate\n•Thiamin\n•Vitamin A\n•Calcium\n•Iron\n•Zinc\n•Fluids
279	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-13 16:43:02.026021	--- 5 - Fat soluble vitamins.pdf ---\nFat soluble vitamins \nFundamentals of Human Nutrition \n1\nVitamin A – Introduction \n•Two groups of compounds have vitamin A activity: \n•Vitamin A  : Retinol, retinaldehyde, and retinoic acid (In \nanimal sources) \n•Provitamin A  : Carotenoids ( β-Carotene) (in plant \nsources) \n2\nFunctions \n•Involve in vision : normal function of retina and \nepithelial carfare of retina \n•Maintain health epithelial cell integrity : cell \ndifferentiation to produce goblet cells \n•Facilitate normal bone growth – maintain the \nfunctions of osteoblast and osteoclast cells \n•Act as antioxidant \n•Synthesis of immune cells \n•Involve in embryonic development and reproduction \n3\nVitamin A and vision \n•The form of Vitamin A in the visual cycle is retinal. \n•Within the eye, 11- cis-retinal is bound to protein \n"opsin" to form rhodospin in rods cells and iodopsin in \ncones cells \n•Rodopsin - vision at dark light \n•Iodopsin – vision at bright light \n•As light enters the eye, the - cis-retinal is converted all \n"trans retinal” (isomarization) \n•The all-"trans retinal dissociates” from the opsin called \nphoto-bleaching. \n4\n5\n6\n7\nSources of Vitamin A \n•Animal sources : meat, fish, liver, milk and milk \nproducts, eggs yolk \n•Plant sources \n•Vegetable oil, dark green & deep yellow F & V \n•Broccoli, spinach, carrots, pumpkin, sweet potatoes, \n•Mangoes, papaya \n8\nVitamin A deficiency \n•Poor vision : night blindness \n•Dry skin \n•Dry eye : Xerophthalmia, Keratomalacia, Bitot’s spot \n•Delay growth \n•Poor wound healing \n•Frequent infections \n•Deformed bones \n9\nBitot’s spot Keratomalacia : The surface of the \nconjunctiva (the membrane that lines \nthe eyelids and covers the white of \nthe eye) and cornea dries, sometimes \nleading to corneal ulcers and bacterial \ninfections and cloudy. The tear glands \nare also affected, resulting in an \ninadequate tear film and dry eyes. \n10\nVitamin D \n•Skin synthesis vitamin D in multi-step process \n•About 90% of vitamin D requirement is supplied by \ncutaneous synthesis \n•Two forms in the diet, \n- Cholecalciferol : D3 – animal sources \n- Ergocalciferol : D2 – plant sources \n11\n\nCutaneous vitamin D synthesis \nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=onSPZ0aBUKM&t=165s \n\nVitamin D Functions \n13\n\n14\n\n15\n\nVit D food Sources \n•Sunlight  - main source, 10 – 20 minutes sun \nexposure 3 - 4 times a day \n•Time vary depending on skin type, genetics \n•Mushrooms (sun grown) \n•Meat, liver, tuna, salmon, sardine, Egg yolk \n•Milk and milk products \n•Fortified foods – milk powder, butter, margarine \n16\n\nVitamin D Deficiency \n•Deficiency = lack of mineral for bone; weakened \nbones, bowed legs \n•Children = Rickets : impaired mineralization of bone \nmatrix in growing skeleton due to low calcium \nabsorption \n•Adults = Osteomalacia : demineralization \n17\n\nVitamin E \nFunctions \n•Antioxidant  - protecting cell membranes and \nplasma lipoproteins from free radical damage \n•Involve in gene expression \n•Neurological functions \n•Regulation of oxidation reduction reactions \n•Maintain cell membrane stability \n18\nSources of Vitamin E \n•Vegetable oils - Sunflower oil, palm oil \n•Nuts \n•Seeds \n•Whole grains \n•Wheat germ \n•Avocado \n•Toxicity and deficiencies are rare \n19\n\nVitamin E Deficiency \n•Ataxia  : lack of voluntary coordination of muscle \nmovements \n•Myopathy – wasting \n•Peripheral neuropathy - damage to nerves \n•Retinopathy \n•Impairment of the immune response \n20\n\nVitamin K \nFunctions \n•Involve in blood clotting \n•Involve in electron transport chain : energy \nproduction \n•Antioxidant \n•Improve bone density :facilitate osteoblast cell \nformation \n21\n22\n\nDeficiency \n•Excessive bleeding – bleeding in intestine, ENT \n(Ear, Norse and Throat) bleeding \n•Poor bone development \n23\n\nSources of Vitamin K \n•Cabbage \n•Mustard \n•Spinach \n•About 1/2 from intestinal bacteria : Vitamin K \ninjection is given at birth \n•Deficiency usually seen when disease or \nchronic antibiotic use \n•K is low in breast milk, therefore vitamin K is \ngiven as injections at birth \n24
