280	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-13 17:06:38.36148	--- 5 - Fat soluble vitamins.pdf ---\nFat soluble vitamins \nFundamentals of Human Nutrition \n1\nVitamin A – Introduction \n•Two groups of compounds have vitamin A activity: \n•Vitamin A  : Retinol, retinaldehyde, and retinoic acid (In \nanimal sources) \n•Provitamin A  : Carotenoids ( β-Carotene) (in plant \nsources) \n2\nFunctions \n•Involve in vision : normal function of retina and \nepithelial carfare of retina \n•Maintain health epithelial cell integrity : cell \ndifferentiation to produce goblet cells \n•Facilitate normal bone growth – maintain the \nfunctions of osteoblast and osteoclast cells \n•Act as antioxidant \n•Synthesis of immune cells \n•Involve in embryonic development and reproduction \n3\nVitamin A and vision \n•The form of Vitamin A in the visual cycle is retinal. \n•Within the eye, 11- cis-retinal is bound to protein \n"opsin" to form rhodospin in rods cells and iodopsin in \ncones cells \n•Rodopsin - vision at dark light \n•Iodopsin – vision at bright light \n•As light enters the eye, the - cis-retinal is converted all \n"trans retinal” (isomarization) \n•The all-"trans retinal dissociates” from the opsin called \nphoto-bleaching. \n4\n5\n6\n7\nSources of Vitamin A \n•Animal sources : meat, fish, liver, milk and milk \nproducts, eggs yolk \n•Plant sources \n•Vegetable oil, dark green & deep yellow F & V \n•Broccoli, spinach, carrots, pumpkin, sweet potatoes, \n•Mangoes, papaya \n8\nVitamin A deficiency \n•Poor vision : night blindness \n•Dry skin \n•Dry eye : Xerophthalmia, Keratomalacia, Bitot’s spot \n•Delay growth \n•Poor wound healing \n•Frequent infections \n•Deformed bones \n9\nBitot’s spot Keratomalacia : The surface of the \nconjunctiva (the membrane that lines \nthe eyelids and covers the white of \nthe eye) and cornea dries, sometimes \nleading to corneal ulcers and bacterial \ninfections and cloudy. The tear glands \nare also affected, resulting in an \ninadequate tear film and dry eyes. \n10\nVitamin D \n•Skin synthesis vitamin D in multi-step process \n•About 90% of vitamin D requirement is supplied by \ncutaneous synthesis \n•Two forms in the diet, \n- Cholecalciferol : D3 – animal sources \n- Ergocalciferol : D2 – plant sources \n11\n\nCutaneous vitamin D synthesis \nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=onSPZ0aBUKM&t=165s \n\nVitamin D Functions \n13\n\n14\n\n15\n\nVit D food Sources \n•Sunlight  - main source, 10 – 20 minutes sun \nexposure 3 - 4 times a day \n•Time vary depending on skin type, genetics \n•Mushrooms (sun grown) \n•Meat, liver, tuna, salmon, sardine, Egg yolk \n•Milk and milk products \n•Fortified foods – milk powder, butter, margarine \n16\n\nVitamin D Deficiency \n•Deficiency = lack of mineral for bone; weakened \nbones, bowed legs \n•Children = Rickets : impaired mineralization of bone \nmatrix in growing skeleton due to low calcium \nabsorption \n•Adults = Osteomalacia : demineralization \n17\n\nVitamin E \nFunctions \n•Antioxidant  - protecting cell membranes and \nplasma lipoproteins from free radical damage \n•Involve in gene expression \n•Neurological functions \n•Regulation of oxidation reduction reactions \n•Maintain cell membrane stability \n18\nSources of Vitamin E \n•Vegetable oils - Sunflower oil, palm oil \n•Nuts \n•Seeds \n•Whole grains \n•Wheat germ \n•Avocado \n•Toxicity and deficiencies are rare \n19\n\nVitamin E Deficiency \n•Ataxia  : lack of voluntary coordination of muscle \nmovements \n•Myopathy – wasting \n•Peripheral neuropathy - damage to nerves \n•Retinopathy \n•Impairment of the immune response \n20\n\nVitamin K \nFunctions \n•Involve in blood clotting \n•Involve in electron transport chain : energy \nproduction \n•Antioxidant \n•Improve bone density :facilitate osteoblast cell \nformation \n21\n22\n\nDeficiency \n•Excessive bleeding – bleeding in intestine, ENT \n(Ear, Norse and Throat) bleeding \n•Poor bone development \n23\n\nSources of Vitamin K \n•Cabbage \n•Mustard \n•Spinach \n•About 1/2 from intestinal bacteria : Vitamin K \ninjection is given at birth \n•Deficiency usually seen when disease or \nchronic antibiotic use \n•K is low in breast milk, therefore vitamin K is \ngiven as injections at birth \n24
