285	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-13 17:27:45.224055	--- 3 - Proteins.pdf ---\nProteins in Human Nutrition \nFundamentals of Human Nutrition \nDr. Thilanka Ranathunga\nDept of Applied Nutrition \n1\n\nLearning objectives \n• Identify the composition of proteins\n•Differentiate essential and non -essential amino acids\n• Describe the role of proteins in human body\n• Describe the health effects of excess and low protein intake \n2\nChemical nature of proteins\n•Composed of C, H, N and O\n•Building block is amino acid (AA) \n•AAs are link together with “ peptide \nbonds ” to form proteins \n•Main function is the formation of body \nstructures\n3\n\nType of AA \n•Mainly two types\n-Essential AA\n-Non Essential AA\nEssential AA (EAA)\n•Total of 8 AA\n•For small children 9 AA\n•Cannot synthesis in the body\nNon essential AA (NEAA)\n•Total of 11\n•Can be synthesized in the body \n4\nEssential Amino Acids  Nonessential Amino Acids  \nHistidine  Alanine  \nIsoleucine  Arginine*  \nLeucine  Asparagine  \nLysine  Aspartic acid  \nMethionine  Cysteine*  \nPhenylalanine  Glutamic acid  \nThreonine  Glutamine*  \nTryptophan  Glycine*  \nValine  Proline*  \n Serine  \n*Conditionally Essential  Tyrosine*  \n Definition of EAA : AAs that cannot be synthesis \nin the body in sufficient amount to meet \nphysiological requirement of the body\nFunctions of proteins \n1.Build body tissues \nEx : Collagen\n2. Repair body tissues \n5\n\n3. Immune functions : Antibodies\n4. Hormones : AA hormones \n(Insulin, ACTH) \n5. Enzymes : All enzymes are proteins\n6\n\n6. Nucleoprotiens (proteins in DNA and RNA) : Histones, Protamine \n7. Muscle contraction : Myosin and actin\n8. Transport oxygen : Hemoglobin \n7\n9. Transport nutrients : lipoproteins, albumin (Ca, Mg, Cu), transferrin (Fe)\n10. Regulate osmatic pressure and fluid balance : albumin, globuline\n8\n\n11. Acid base balance : act as buffer : histidine, hemoglobin,  \nalbumin \n9\n\n12. Growth of the fetus\n13. Supply energy at starvation : 4 kcal/g\n10\n\nProtein denaturation \n•Destruction of protein structure\n•By HCL in the stomach, bases, heat\n•Part of protein digestion \n•Denatured proteins can access to protiolytic\nenzymes easily\n•Cooking > apply heat > denaturation > important \nfor quick digestion \n11\n\nAnimal protein sources\n•High quality proteins\n•Provide all AAs\n•Complete proteins\n•High bioavailability \n•Meat, fish, eggs, milk\n12\n\nPlant food sources \n•Low in quality\n•Incomplete proteins\n•Do not contain all essential AA\n•Need to combine food items to make the diet complete\nEg: -Soy, pulses, nuts, legumes, cereals \n•Poor absorption of AAs\n13\n\nNitrogen balance\n•Body maintain the same amount of protein in  tissues for day today\nworks\n•N balance = N intake –Nloss\n-Losses = Urine + feces +skin\n-N intake = food andbeverages\n•N balance = +ve, -ve,zero\n• + ve = during growth (in children, fetus, pregnant mothers)\n•-ve=at illness, wasting, starvation, burns, injuries,  infections\n\nHealth effects ofproteins\nExcess consumption\n•Heart diseases -Protein rich foods are rich in  saturated fats\n•Cancers –colon, breast, kidney\n•Osteoporosis -increase Ca excretion due to high P  content in \nproteins \n•Obesity –protein rich foods are naturally rich in fats\nKwashiorkor vsMarusmusLowconsumption\nRecommended intake ofproteins
169	1	\N	AI Quiz - Easy - 2026-03-21 20:27	Generated from 1 file(s)	1	1800	easy	2026-03-21 20:27:21.161242	Object-Oriented Programming Concepts\n\nClasses and Objects:\nA class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines attributes (data) and methods (functions).\nAn object is an instance of a class with actual values.\n\nExample:\nclass Car:\n    def __init__(self, brand, model):\n        self.brand = brand\n        self.model = model\n\nInheritance:\nInheritance allows a class to inherit attributes and methods from another class.\nThe child class can override methods or add new ones.\n\nPolymorphism:\nPolymorphism allows methods to behave differently based on the object calling them.\nThis is achieved through method overriding and interfaces.\n\nEncapsulation:\nEncapsulation restricts direct access to object data.\nUse private attributes (prefix with __) and provide getter/setter methods.\n\nAbstraction:\nAbstraction hides complex implementation details and shows only essential features.\nUse abstract base classes to define interfaces.
