246	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-11 22:12:52.521343	--- 5 - Core concepts of OOP.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 5\n\nThe four core concepts OOP\n•Encapsulation\n•Inheritance\n•Polymorphism\n•Abstraction\nEncapsulation\n•Encapsulation is a mechanism where you bind your data and code together as a single unit. \n•It also means to hide your data to make it safe from any modification. \n•Can achieve data hiding and controlled access.\n•The best way to understand encapsulation is to look at the example of a medical capsule , where \nthe drug is always safe inside the capsule. \n•Similarly, through encapsulation the methods and variables of a class are well hidden and safe.\n\n•We can achieve encapsulation in Java by:\nDeclaring the variables of a class as private .\nProviding public setter and getter methods to modify and view the variables values.\nAdvantages\n•Data hiding : If there are no getters, we cannot see the data. \n•Immutability : If there are no setters, we can’t change the data it is called as immutability. \n•Data validation : We can only check the value by using setters. This is called as data validation \nInheritance\n•Inheritance is a mechanism in which one class acquires (inherits) the properties and behaviors \n(fields and methods) of another class.\n•Inheritance is the process of creating sub classes from the existing base class . The sub class able to \naccess most of the members(excluding private type members) from its base class and include its \nown members.\n•It promotes code reusability and helps establish a natural parent –child relationship between \nclasses.\n•A child inherits certain characteristics (like eye color, blood group) from parents. Similarly, in Java, \nthere are two classes:\n1. Parent class ( Super class or Base class)\n2. Child class (Sub class or Derived class )\n•A class which inherits the properties is known as Child Class whereas a class whose properties are \ninherited is known as Parent class.\n•Inheritance is further classified into 4 types:\nSingle Inheritance\nMultilevel Inheritance\nHierarchical Inheritance\nMultiple inheritance (Not supported by Java)\nSingle Inheritance\n•In single inheritance, one class inherits the properties and behavior of another. \n•It enables a derived class to inherit the properties and behavior from a single parent class.\n•Let’s see the syntax for single inheritance:\nclass A\n{\n}\nclass B extends A {\n}\nMultilevel Inheritance\n•Having more than one parent class but at different levels , such type of inheritance is called \nMultilevel Inheritance.\n•Let’s see the syntax for multilevel inheritance in Java:\nclass A{\n}\nclass B extends A{\n}\nclass C extends B{\n}\nHierarchical Inheritance\n•When a class has more than one child classes (sub classes), then such kind of inheritance is known as \nhierarchical inheritance.\n•Let’s see the syntax for hierarchical inheritance in Java:\nclass A{\n}\nclass B extends A{\n}\nclass C extends A{\n}\nSingle, Multilevel, and Hierarchical    \nInheritances\n•The Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical Inheritances maintain " is a" relationship between the base class \nand the sub class.\n•This relation enable a subclass to legally access the members from its base class.\n•The term " is a" refers to " extends " keyword in Java.\n•"extends" keyword creates a legal relation between base and sub class.\n•That's why Java accepts Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical Inheritances.\nMultiple inheritance\n•Multiple inheritance is not supported by Java as it because it can lead to ambiguity problems (e.g., \nthe diamond problem).\n•This type of inheritance can only be achieved by the interfaces .\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism means taking many forms , where ‘poly’ means many and ‘morph’ means forms . \n•It is the ability of a variable, function or object to take on multiple forms. \n•In other words, polymorphism allows you define one interface or method and have multiple \nimplementations.\nLet’s consider this real -world scenario of \nmusical instruments!\n•Weknow that there aredifferent types ofinstruments such as\nGuitar, Piano, and Drum .Imagine there isaparent class called\nInstrument, and ithas three child classes :Guitar, Piano, and\nDrum .The parent class contains amethod playSound (),which is\ninherited byallchild classes .Now, asweallknow, aGuitar\nproduces sound differently compared toaPiano oraDrum .The\nGuitar willstrum strings, thePiano willplay keys, and theDrum\nwill create beats .Although allthree classes inherit the same\nmethod name playSound (),their implementation iscompletely\ndifferent depending onthetype ofinstrument .\n•The point ofthis discussion isthat asingle method name can\ntake multiple forms .The same method (playSound ())behaves\ndifferently depending onwhich object calls it.\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism in Java is of two types:\nCompile time polymorphism\nRun time polymorphism\nCompile time polymorphism\n•Compile -time polymorphism happens when multiple methods in the same class share the same \nname but differ in their parameter list (number of parameters or type of parameters).\n•The decision of which method to call is made by the compiler at compile time, not at runtime.\nRun time polymorphism\n•Runtime polymorphism happens when a subclass provides its own implementation of a method \nthat is already defined in its superclass.\n•Which version of the method gets executed is determined at runtime based on the object being \nreferred to, not the reference type.\nAbstraction\n•Abstraction is the process of hiding the internal implementation details and showing only the \nessential features to the user.\n•You can achieve abstraction in two ways:\nAbstract Class\nInterface\nSummary \n✓Encapsulation → Bundling data (attributes) and methods together\n✓Inheritance → Child class inherits properties & behaviors from parent class; promotes code reuse.\nTypes: Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical (Multiple via interfaces only).\n✓Polymorphism → One name, many forms.\nCompile -time → Method Overloading.\nRuntime → Method Overriding.\n✓Abstraction → Hiding internal details, showing only essential features.\nAchieved using abstract classes and interfaces.\n✓Real -world examples:\nEncapsulation → Medical capsule.\nInheritance → Child inherits eye color from parents.\nPolymorphism → Different instruments playing sound differently.
247	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-11 22:32:46.18398	--- 6 - Interfaces.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 6\nOutline\n•Interface\n•Why Interfaces are Important?\n•Multiple Interfaces\n•Multiple Inheritance in Java Using Interface\n•Newer Features for Interfaces (Java 8 and Later)\n•Difference Between Class and Interface\n•Abstract class\n•"final" Keyword in Java\n•Final class\n•Wrapper class\n•Autoboxing & Unboxing in Java\nWhat you know?\n•Data abstraction is the process of hiding certain details and showing only essential information to \nthe user.\n•Abstraction can be achieved with either abstract classes or interfaces.\nInterface\n•An interface in Java is a blueprint of a behavior . \n•Contains static constants and abstract methods.\n•To declare an interface, use the interface keyword. \n•To implement the interface, use the implements keyword.\n•An interface cannot contain a constructor (as it cannot be used to create objects)\n•Format:\ninterface < interface_name >{\n<final_variables >\n<abstract_methods >\n}\n•Key Properties of Interface:\nBy default, variables in an interface are public, static and final .\nIt is used to achieve abstraction and multiple inheritance in Java.\nWhy Interfaces are Important?\n•Make Code Abstract: You only see what methods are available. This makes your code simpler to use \nbecause you do not need to know the inner workings.\n•Allow Multiple Behaviors: Interfaces let a single class act like it has many kinds of behaviors. This is \na very powerful way to design your programs.\n•Help with Loose Connections: This means that classes depend on the rules defined by interfaces, \nnot on specific ways things are built. \nMultiple Interfaces\n•To implement multiple interfaces, separate them with a comma.\n•Note: A class can extend another class and similarly, an interface can extend another interface. \nHowever, only a class can implement an interface and the reverse (an interface implementing a \nclass) is not allowed.\nMultiple Inheritance in Java Using \nInterface\n•Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes to avoid ambiguity, but it supports multiple \ninheritance using interfaces.\n\nNewer Features for Interfaces (Java 8 \nand Later)\n•Java versions 8 and newer added new features to interfaces. These changes make interfaces more \npowerful for developers. They help you reuse code and write less repeated code.\nDefault Methods\nStatic Methods\nPrivate Methods (Java 9 and later)\nFind out the key difference between class \nand interface.\nDifference Between Class and Interface\nClass Interface\nCan create an object In an interface, you can't create an object\nSupports both instance and static variables Only supports public static final variables\nIt doesn't support multiple inheritance Supports multiple inheritance\nCan have constructors No constructors allowed\nDefined using class keyword Defined using interface keyword\nAbstract class\n•Restricted class that cannot be used to create objects.\n•We define the class using abstract keyword .\n•An abstract class can have both abstract and non abstract methods.\n•Rules for Java Abstract class\nAn abstract class must be declared using the abstract keyword.\nAbstract classes can include abstract and non -abstract methods.\nAn Abstract Class cannot be instantiated.\nThey can include constructors.\nCan includes static methods and final methods.\nAbstract Classes Vs Interfaces\nAbstract Classes Vs Interfaces\nAbstract Classes Interfaces\nCannot be directly created as an object and can \ncontain abstract methodsA blueprint for a class that contains only abstract \nmethods (before Java 8) and constant variables\nCan have methods with code and methods without \ncodeCan only have methods without code (before Java 8), \nAfter Java 8, can also have methods with default code, \nstatic methods, and private methods\nCan have special methods to create objects \n(constructors)Cannot have special methods to create objects \n(constructors).\nA class can only extend one abstract class A class can implement many interfaces\nMethods and variables can have different access levels, \nlike public, private, protectedMethods and variables are always public\nAbstract class is for “is -a” relationship with shared code Interface is for defining capabilities/behaviors (like \n“can -do” contract)\n"final" Keyword in Java\n•The final keyword in Java is a non-access modifier used to prevent modification. \n•It can be applied to variables (value cannot change), methods (cannot be overridden) and classes \n(cannot be extended).\nFinal variable ----> To create constant variable\nFinal method ---> Prevent method overriding\nFinal class ---> Prevent inheritance\nFinal class\n•When a class is declared with the final keyword in Java, it is called a final class. A final class cannot \nbe extended(inherited). \n•All wrapper classes in Java are final classes, such as String, Integer, etc. Any subclass cannot inherit \nfinal class\n•There are two uses of a final class: \nTo prevent inheritance , as final classes cannot be extended.\nTo create an immutable class\n•Advantage of the Final Class\nThe Final class provides security as it cannot be extended or inherited by any other class. Classes \nthat can be extended can leak potential users' sensitive data, but final classes make data \nelements safe and secure.\nThe final class is complete and immutable, so external access does not change data elements .\nWrapper class\n•Wrapper class provides a mechanism to convert primitive data types into wrapper class objects.\n•Following are the equivalent wrapper class objects of primitive data types.\n•Primitive Data Type          Wrapper Class\nbyte Byte\nshort Short\nint Integer\nlong Long\nfloat Float\ndouble Double\nboolean Boolean\nchar Character\n•To create a wrapper object, use the wrapper class.\nAutoboxing and Unboxing in Java\n•Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive data type into its corresponding wrapper \nclass object.\n•Introduced in Java 5 to simplify coding.\n•Unboxing is the reverse process: converting a wrapper class object back into its primitive type.\nActivity\n•1. Which of the following statements about abstract classes in Java is true?\na) Abstract classes cannot have any methods with implementations.\nb) Abstract classes cannot be instantiated.\nc) Abstract classes can only contain abstract methods.\nd) Abstract classes cannot have constructors.\n•2. Can an abstract class have static methods in Java?\na) Yes, but they cannot be called.\nb) No, static methods are not allowed in abstract classes.\nc) Yes, and they can be called without creating an instance of the class.\nd) No, because static methods must have a body.\n•3. Which keyword is used to declare a class as abstract in Java?\na) abstract\nb) Abstract\nc) final\nd) static\n•4. In Java, can an abstract class implement an interface without providing implementations for all \nits methods?\na) Yes, the abstract class can leave the implementation to its subclasses.\nb) No, it must provide implementations for all interface methods.\nc) Yes, but only if the interface has default methods.\nd) No, abstract classes cannot implement interfaces.\n•5. What is the outcome if a final method is attempted to be overridden in a subclass?\na) The code will compile, but the superclass method will be executed.\nb) The code will compile, and the subclass method will be executed.\nc) The code will result in a compilation error.\nd) The code will compile but will throw an exception at runtime.\n•6. What will happen if you try to change the value of a final variable after it has been initialized?   \npublic class Test {  \npublic static void main(String[] args) {  \nfinal int x = 10;  \nx = 20;  \n}  \n}    \na) Value will change to 20\nb) Compilation error\nc) Runtime error\nd) The program will run but the value will remain 10\n•7. Which of the following statements about the final keyword is true?\na) A final class can be subclassed.\nb) A final method can be overridden.\nc) A final variable must be initialized when declared.\nd) A final variable can be assigned a value only once.\n•8. Which of the following is a valid way to create an Integer object with the value 10?\nInteger val= new Integer(10);\nInteger val= Integer.valueOf (10);\nInteger val= 10;\nint val= 10;\n•9. What is the purpose of autoboxing in Java?\nConverting an object to its corresponding primitive data type.\nConverting a primitive data type to its corresponding object.\nConverting between different types of wrapper classes.\nConverting a string to its numeric equivalent.\nSummary \n✓Interface\nBlueprint of behavior → contains abstract methods & constants\nUsed for abstraction and multiple inheritance\n✓Why Interfaces are Important?\nMake code abstract → hide details\nAllow multiple behaviors (multiple inheritance)\nHelp with loose coupling between classes\n✓Abstract Class\nDeclared with abstract keyword\nCan have abstract and non -abstract methods\nCan include constructors\nCannot be instantiated\nSummary \n✓Final Keyword\nFinal variable → constant (value cannot change)\nFinal method → cannot be overridden\nFinal class → cannot be inherited\n✓Wrapper Classes\nConvert primitives → objects (e.g., int → Integer)\nNeeded for collections like ArrayList\nAll wrapper classes are final\n✓Autoboxing & Unboxing\nAutoboxing: primitive → wrapper object (automatic)\nUnboxing: wrapper object → primitive (automatic)
