reverse (an interface implementing a \nclass) is not allowed.\nMultiple Inheritance in Java Using \nInterface\n•Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes to avoid ambiguity, but it supports multiple \ninheritance using interfaces.\n\nNewer Features for Interfaces (Java 8 \nand Later)\n•Java versions 8 and newer added new features to interfaces. These changes make interfaces more \npowerful for developers. They help you reuse code and write less repeated code.\nDefault Methods\nStatic Methods\nPrivate Methods (Java 9 and later)\nFind out the key difference between class \nand interface.\nDifference Between Class and Interface\nClass Interface\nCan create an object In an interface, you can't create an object\nSupports both instance and static variables Only supports public static final variables\nIt doesn't support multiple inheritance Supports multiple inheritance\nCan have constructors No constructors allowed\nDefined using class keyword Defined using interface keyword\nAbstract class\n•Restricted class that cannot be used to create objects.\n•We define the class using abstract keyword .\n•An abstract class can have both abstract and non abstract methods.\n•Rules for Java Abstract class\nAn abstract class must be declared using the abstract keyword.\nAbstract classes can include abstract and non -abstract methods.\nAn Abstract Class cannot be instantiated.\nThey can include constructors.\nCan includes static methods and final methods.\nAbstract Classes Vs Interfaces\nAbstract Classes Vs Interfaces\nAbstract Classes Interfaces\nCannot be directly created as an object and can \ncontain abstract methodsA blueprint for a class that contains only abstract \nmethods (before Java 8) and constant variables\nCan have methods with code and methods without \ncodeCan only have methods without code (before Java 8), \nAfter Java 8, can also have methods with default code, \nstatic methods, and private methods\nCan have special methods to create objects \n(constructors)Cannot have special methods to create objects \n(constructors).\nA class can only extend one abstract class A class can implement many interfaces\nMethods and variables can have different access levels, \nlike public, private, protectedMethods and variables are always public\nAbstract class is for “is -a” relationship with shared code Interface is for defining capabilities/behaviors (like \n“can -do” contract)\n"final" Keyword in Java\n•The final keyword in Java is a non-access modifier used to prevent modification. \n•It can be applied to variables (value cannot change), methods (cannot be overridden) and classes \n(cannot be extended).\nFinal variable ----> To create constant variable\nFinal method ---> Prevent method overriding\nFinal class ---> Prevent inheritance\nFinal class\n•When a class is declared with the final keyword in Java, it is called a final class. A final class cannot \nbe extended(inherited). \n•All wrapper classes in Java are final classes, such as String, Integer, etc. Any subclass cannot inherit \nfinal class\n•There are two uses of a final class: \nTo prevent inheritance , as final classes cannot be extended.\nTo create an immutable class\n•Advantage of the Final Class\nThe Final class provides security as it cannot be extended or inherited by any other class. Classes \nthat can be extended can leak potential users' sensitive data, but final classes make data \nelements safe and secure.\nThe final class is complete and immutable, so external access does not change data elements .\nWrapper class\n•Wrapper class provides a mechanism to convert primitive data types into wrapper class objects.\n•Following are the equivalent wrapper class objects of primitive data types.\n•Primitive Data Type          Wrapper Class\nbyte Byte\nshort Short\nint Integer\nlong Long\nfloat Float\ndouble Double\nboolean Boolean\nchar Character\n•To create a wrapper object, use the wrapper class.\nAutoboxing and Unboxing in Java\n•Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive data type into its corresponding wrapper \nclass object.\n•Introduced in Java 5 to simplify coding.\n•Unboxing is the reverse process: converting a wrapper class object back into its primitive type.\nActivity\n•1. Which of the following statements about abstract classes in Java is true?\na) Abstract classes cannot have any methods with implementations.\nb) Abstract classes cannot be instantiated.\nc) Abstract classes can only contain abstract methods.\nd) Abstract classes cannot have constructors.\n•2. Can an abstract class have static methods in Java?\na) Yes, but they cannot be called.\nb) No, static methods are not allowed in abstract classes.\nc) Yes, and they can be called without creating an instance of the class.\nd) No, because static methods must have a body.\n•3. Which keyword is used to declare a class as abstract in Java?\na) abstract\nb) Abstract\nc) final\nd) static\n•4. In Java, can an abstract class implement an interface without providing implementations for all \nits methods?\na) Yes, the abstract class can leave the implementation to its subclasses.\nb) No, it must provide implementations for all interface methods.\nc) Yes, but only if the interface has default methods.\nd) No, abstract classes cannot implement interfaces.\n•5. What is the outcome if a final method is attempted to be overridden in a subclass?\na) The code will compile, but the superclass method will be executed.\nb) The code will compile, and the subclass method will be executed.\nc) The code will result in a compilation error.\nd) The code will compile but will throw an exception at runtime.\n•6. What will happen if you try to change the value of a final variable after it has been initialized?   \npublic class Test {  \npublic static void main(String[] args) {  \nfinal int x = 10;  \nx = 20;  \n}  \n}    \na) Value will change to 20\nb) Compilation error\nc) Runtime error\nd) The program will run but the value will remain 10\n•7. Which of the following statements about the final keyword is true?\na) A final class can be subclassed.\nb) A final method can be overridden.\nc) A final variable must be initialized when declared.\nd) A final variable can be assigned a value only once.\n•8. Which of the following is a valid way to create an Integer object with the value 10?\nInteger val= new Integer(10);\nInteger val= Integer.valueOf (10);\nInteger val= 10;\nint val= 10;\n•9. What is the purpose of autoboxing in Java?\nConverting an object to its corresponding primitive data type.\nConverting a primitive data type to its corresponding object.\nConverting between different types of wrapper classes.\nConverting a string to its numeric equivalent.\nSummary \n✓Interface\nBlueprint of behavior → contains abstract methods & constants\nUsed for abstraction and multiple inheritance\n✓Why Interfaces are Important?\nMake code abstract → hide details\nAllow multiple behaviors (multiple inheritance)\nHelp with loose coupling between classes\n✓Abstract Class\nDeclared with abstract keyword\nCan have abstract and non -abstract methods\nCan include constructors\nCannot be instantiated\nSummary \n✓Final Keyword\nFinal variable → constant (value cannot change)\nFinal method → cannot be overridden\nFinal class → cannot be inherited\n✓Wrapper Classes\nConvert primitives → objects (e.g., int → Integer)\nNeeded for collections like ArrayList\nAll wrapper classes are final\n✓Autoboxing & Unboxing\nAutoboxing: primitive → wrapper object (automatic)\nUnboxing: wrapper object → primitive (automatic)
249	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-11 22:39:21.449614	--- 7 -  String class.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 7\n\nOutline\n•Introduction to String class\n•How to Create Java Strings?\n•How Strings are Stored in Memory\n•Java String Methods\n•String Immutability\n•Differences between StringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  in Java\n•Strings with Special Characters\nIntroduction to String class\n•Represents a sequence of characters . \n•A Java String is an ordered, immutable sequence of characters. \n•Immutability means you cannot change a String object after you create it.\n•For example, “hello” or “Java” are strings. \n•String class in java lang package, is used to create string objects.\nHow to Create Java Strings?\n•There are two ways to create a String object:\n•1. Use String Literals \n•This is the most common way to create a String. \n•Java treats text in double quotes as a String literal.\nString s1 = "Welcome";\nString s2 = "Welcome"; // refers to the same object in String Pool\nSystem.out.println (s1 == s2);  \n•2. Use the new Keyword \n•Java String is created by using a keyword “ new ”.\n•Example: String s=new String(“Welcome”);  \nString s3 = new String("Welcome");\nString s4 = new String("Welcome");\nSystem.out.println (s3 == s4); \nHow Strings are Stored in Memory\nString literal\n•Whenever a String Object is created as a literal, the object will be created in the String constant \npool. \n•The string constant pool is present in the heap memory.\n•Example 1: Using String literals to assigning char sequence value.\nString str1 = "Hello";\n•Example 2: When we initialize the same char sequence using string literals.\nString str1 = "Hello";\nString str2 = "Hello";\n•str2 will refer the same object "Hello" in the String constant pool, it will not be created again the \nSting constant pool (Two different references but same object).\n•It means, Java stores String literals in the String Pool. If you create the same String literal twice, \nJava points both variables to the same object in the pool.\nUsing new Keyword\n•The string can also be declared using a new keyword (dynamically allocated). \n•In case of String are dynamically allocated they are assigned a new memory location in the heap . \nThis string will not be added to the String constant pool .\n•Example 1: Using new keyword to assign a char sequence to a String object.\nString str3 = new String(“Hello"); \nString str4 = new String(“Hello");\nJava String Methods\n•Java provides methods to work with Strings. \n•These methods manipulate and analyze text.\n•length()                                               \n•concat () \n•charAt ()\n•equals()\n•equalsIgnoreCase ()\n•indexOf ()\n•substring()\n•replace()\n•toLowerCase ()\n•toUpperCase ()\n•trim()\n•compareTo ()\n•valueOf ()•contains()\n•toCharArray ()\n•isEmpty ()\n•endsWith ()\n•1. Get String Length\nThe length() method returns the number of characters in a String.\n•2. Concatenate Strings\nYou can join two or more Strings. Use the + operator or the concat () method.\n•3. Access Characters\nUse the charAt () method to get a character at a specific index. Indexes start from 0.\n•4. Compare Strings\nThe equals() method compares two Strings. It checks if their content is the same. Use \nequalsIgnoreCase () to ignore case differences.\nDo not use == to compare String content. The == operator checks if two String references point \nto the same object in memory.\n•5. Find Substrings\nThe indexOf () method finds the first occurrence of a substring. It returns the index. If the \nsubstring is not found, it returns -1.\n•6. Extract Substrings\nThe substring() method extracts a portion of a String. You provide start and end indexes.\n•7. Replace Characters or Substrings\nUse replace() to replace characters or substrings.\n•8. Convert Case\nThe toLowerCase () and toUpperCase () methods change the case of a String.\n•9. Trim Whitespace\nThe trim() method removes leading and trailing whitespace.\nActivity\n1.\nString name = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (name.length ()); \n2.\nString s1 = "Hello";\nString s2 = "World";\nSystem.out.println (s1.concat(" " + s2)); \nSystem.out.println (s1 + " " + s2);       \n3.\nString text = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (text.charAt (2)); \n4.\nString a = "Hello";\nString b = "hello";\nSystem.out.println (a.equals (b));            \nSystem.out.println (a.equalsIgnoreCase (b));  \n5.\nString text = "banana";\nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("a"));  \nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("na")); \n6.\nString word = "Programming";\nSystem.out.println (word.substring (0, 4));\n7.\nString name = "car";\nSystem.out.println (name.replace ('c', 'b')); \n8.\nString word = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (word.toUpperCase ()); \nSystem.out.println (word.toLowerCase ()); \n9.\nString s = "  Hello Java  ";\nSystem.out.println (s.trim ()); \n10.\nString s1 = "apple";\nString s2 = "apple";\nSystem.out.println (s1.compareTo(s2));\nString name = "   Java Programming   ";\nSystem.out.println (name.trim ().substring(0, 4). toUpperCase ());\nString Immutability\nString str = "Java";\nstr.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); \nWhat will be the output? why?\n•Output: Java     //Not "Java Programming"\n•Because concat () creates a new String object, it doesn’t modify the original.\n•To store the new value, assign it back:\nString str = "Java";\nstr = str.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); // Output: Java Programming\n•Unlike other data types in Java, Strings are immutable. \n•It means that Strings are constant, their values cannot be changed after they are created.\n•New String is created whenever we do String manipulation. \n•The original String remains unchanged.\nThis immutability offers benefits:\n1. Thread Safety : Multiple threads can access a String without synchronization problems. One thread \ncannot change a String while another reads it.\n2. Security : Immutability is important for security. When you use Strings for sensitive data like \ndatabase credentials, their unchanging nature prevents unintended modifications.\n3. Performance : The String Pool relies on immutability. This helps save memory and improves \nperformance by reusing existing String objects.\nWhat will be the output?\nString s = “Colombo";\ns.concat (" City");\nSystem.out.println (s); \nStringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(“Colombo");\nsb.append (" City");\nSystem.out.println (sb); \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•As String manipulations are resource consuming, Java provides two utility classes: StringBuffer  and \nStringBuilder.\n•StringBuffer  and StringBuilder are mutable classes . \nExample1:\nStringBuffer  sb = new StringBuffer ("Hello");\nsb.append (" World");\nSystem.out.println (sb); // Hello World\nExample2:\nStringBuilder sb2 = new StringBuilder("Java");\nsb2.append(" Rocks");\nSystem.out.println (sb2); // Java Rocks\nFind out the key difference between \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder classes.\n \nStringBuffer StringBuilder\nOperations are thread -safe and synchronized Not thread -safe are not -synchronized\nUsed when multiple threads are working on the same \nString Used in a single -threaded environment\nPerformance is slower when compared to StringBuilder Performance is faster when compared to StringBuffer\nSyntax: StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Hello”); Syntax: StringBuilder var = new StringBuilder(“Hello”);\nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  \nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer\n•The differences between String, StringBuffer , and StringBuilder are based on the following two \nparameters:\nMutability\nPerformance\nString StringBuffer StringBuilder\nString Pool Heap Heap\nImmutable Mutable Mutable\nNot used in a threaded \nenvironmentUsed in a multi -threaded environment Used in a single -threaded \nenvironment\nSlow Slower than StringBuilder but faster than \nStringFaster than StringBuffer\nString var =“Java”; \nString var=newString(“Java”); StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Java"); StringBuilder var = new \nStringBuilder(“Java");\nStrings with Special Characters\n•The backslash ( \\) escape character turns special characters into string characters\n•System.out.println ("She said, \\"Java is fun! \\"");\n•System.out.println ("Path: C: \\\\Program Files \\\\Java");Escape character Result Description\n\\' ' Single quote\n\\" " Double quote\n\\\\ \\ Backslash
250	1	\N	Medium Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated medium level quiz	10	30	medium	2026-04-11 22:45:20.285756	--- 7 -  String class.pdf ---\r\nFundamentals of \r\nobject -oriented programming\r\nLecture 7\r\n\r\nOutline\r\n•Introduction to String class\r\n•How to Create Java Strings?\r\n•How Strings are Stored in Memory\r\n•Java String Methods\r\n•String Immutability\r\n•Differences between StringBuffer  and StringBuilder\r\n•String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  in Java\r\n•Strings with Special Characters\r\nIntroduction to String class\r\n•Represents a sequence of characters . \r\n•A Java String is an ordered, immutable sequence of characters. \r\n•Immutability means you cannot change a String object after you create it.\r\n•For example, “hello” or “Java” are strings. \r\n•String class in java lang package, is used to create string objects.\r\nHow to Create Java Strings?\r\n•There are two ways to create a String object:\r\n•1. Use String Literals \r\n•This is the most common way to create a String. \r\n•Java treats text in double quotes as a String literal.\r\nString s1 = "Welcome";\r\nString s2 = "Welcome"; // refers to the same object in String Pool\r\nSystem.out.println (s1 == s2);  \r\n•2. Use the new Keyword \r\n•Java String is created by using a keyword “ new ”.\r\n•Example: String s=new String(“Welcome”);  \r\nString s3 = new String("Welcome");\r\nString s4 = new String("Welcome");\r\nSystem.out.println (s3 == s4); \r\nHow Strings are Stored in Memory\r\nString literal\r\n•Whenever a String Object is created as a literal, the object will be created in the String constant \r\npool. \r\n•The string constant pool is present in the heap memory.\r\n•Example 1: Using String literals to assigning char sequence value.\r\nString str1 = "Hello";\r\n•Example 2: When we initialize the same char sequence using string literals.\r\nString str1 = "Hello";\r\nString str2 = "Hello";\r\n•str2 will refer the same object "Hello" in the String constant pool, it will not be created again the \r\nSting constant pool (Two different references but same object).\r\n•It means, Java stores String literals in the String Pool. If you create the same String literal twice, \r\nJava points both variables to the same object in the pool.\r\nUsing new Keyword\r\n•The string can also be declared using a new keyword (dynamically allocated). \r\n•In case of String are dynamically allocated they are assigned a new memory location in the heap . \r\nThis string will not be added to the String constant pool .\r\n•Example 1: Using new keyword to assign a char sequence to a String object.\r\nString str3 = new String(“Hello"); \r\nString str4 = new String(“Hello");\r\nJava String Methods\r\n•Java provides methods to work with Strings. \r\n•These methods manipulate and analyze text.\r\n•length()                                               \r\n•concat () \r\n•charAt ()\r\n•equals()\r\n•equalsIgnoreCase ()\r\n•indexOf ()\r\n•substring()\r\n•replace()\r\n•toLowerCase ()\r\n•toUpperCase ()\r\n•trim()\r\n•compareTo ()\r\n•valueOf ()•contains()\r\n•toCharArray ()\r\n•isEmpty ()\r\n•endsWith ()\r\n•1. Get String Length\r\nThe length() method returns the number of characters in a String.\r\n•2. Concatenate Strings\r\nYou can join two or more Strings. Use the + operator or the concat () method.\r\n•3. Access Characters\r\nUse the charAt () method to get a character at a specific index. Indexes start from 0.\r\n•4. Compare Strings\r\nThe equals() method compares two Strings. It checks if their content is the same. Use \r\nequalsIgnoreCase () to ignore case differences.\r\nDo not use == to compare String content. The == operator checks if two String references point \r\nto the same object in memory.\r\n•5. Find Substrings\r\nThe indexOf () method finds the first occurrence of a substring. It returns the index. If the \r\nsubstring is not found, it returns -1.\r\n•6. Extract Substrings\r\nThe substring() method extracts a portion of a String. You provide start and end indexes.\r\n•7. Replace Characters or Substrings\r\nUse replace() to replace characters or substrings.\r\n•8. Convert Case\r\nThe toLowerCase () and toUpperCase () methods change the case of a String.\r\n•9. Trim Whitespace\r\nThe trim() method removes leading and trailing whitespace.\r\nActivity\r\n1.\r\nString name = "Java";\r\nSystem.out.println (name.length ()); \r\n2.\r\nString s1 = "Hello";\r\nString s2 = "World";\r\nSystem.out.println (s1.concat(" " + s2)); \r\nSystem.out.println (s1 + " " + s2);       \r\n3.\r\nString text = "Java";\r\nSystem.out.println (text.charAt (2)); \r\n4.\r\nString a = "Hello";\r\nString b = "hello";\r\nSystem.out.println (a.equals (b));            \r\nSystem.out.println (a.equalsIgnoreCase (b));  \r\n5.\r\nString text = "banana";\r\nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("a"));  \r\nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("na")); \r\n6.\r\nString word = "Programming";\r\nSystem.out.println (word.substring (0, 4));\r\n7.\r\nString name = "car";\r\nSystem.out.println (name.replace ('c', 'b')); \r\n8.\r\nString word = "Java";\r\nSystem.out.println (word.toUpperCase ()); \r\nSystem.out.println (word.toLowerCase ()); \r\n9.\r\nString s = "  Hello Java  ";\r\nSystem.out.println (s.trim ()); \r\n10.\r\nString s1 = "apple";\r\nString s2 = "apple";\r\nSystem.out.println (s1.compareTo(s2));\r\nString name = "   Java Programming   ";\r\nSystem.out.println (name.trim ().substring(0, 4). toUpperCase ());\r\nString Immutability\r\nString str = "Java";\r\nstr.concat (" Programming");\r\nSystem.out.println (str); \r\nWhat will be the output? why?\r\n•Output: Java     //Not "Java Programming"\r\n•Because concat () creates a new String object, it doesn’t modify the original.\r\n•To store the new value, assign it back:\r\nString str = "Java";\r\nstr = str.concat (" Programming");\r\nSystem.out.println (str); // Output: Java Programming\r\n•Unlike other data types in Java, Strings are immutable. \r\n•It means that Strings are constant, their values cannot be changed after they are created.\r\n•New String is created whenever we do String manipulation. \r\n•The original String remains unchanged.\r\nThis immutability offers benefits:\r\n1. Thread Safety : Multiple threads can access a String without synchronization problems. One thread \r\ncannot change a String while another reads it.\r\n2. Security : Immutability is important for security. When you use Strings for sensitive data like \r\ndatabase credentials, their unchanging nature prevents unintended modifications.\r\n3. Performance : The String Pool relies on immutability. This helps save memory and improves \r\nperformance by reusing existing String objects.\r\nWhat will be the output?\r\nString s = “Colombo";\r\ns.concat (" City");\r\nSystem.out.println (s); \r\nStringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(“Colombo");\r\nsb.append (" City");\r\nSystem.out.println (sb); \r\nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder\r\n•As String manipulations are resource consuming, Java provides two utility classes: StringBuffer  and \r\nStringBuilder.\r\n•StringBuffer  and StringBuilder are mutable classes . \r\nExample1:\r\nStringBuffer  sb = new StringBuffer ("Hello");\r\nsb.append (" World");\r\nSystem.out.println (sb); // Hello World\r\nExample2:\r\nStringBuilder sb2 = new StringBuilder("Java");\r\nsb2.append(" Rocks");\r\nSystem.out.println (sb2); // Java Rocks\r\nFind out the key difference between \r\nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder classes.\r\n \r\nStringBuffer StringBuilder\r\nOperations are thread -safe and synchronized Not thread -safe are not -synchronized\r\nUsed when multiple threads are working on the same \r\nString Used in a single -threaded environment\r\nPerformance is slower when compared to StringBuilder Performance is faster when compared to StringBuffer\r\nSyntax: StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Hello”); Syntax: StringBuilder var = new StringBuilder(“Hello”);\r\nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  \r\nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer\r\n•The differences between String, StringBuffer , and StringBuilder are based on the following two \r\nparameters:\r\nMutability\r\nPerformance\r\nString StringBuffer StringBuilder\r\nString Pool Heap Heap\r\nImmutable Mutable Mutable\r\nNot used in a threaded \r\nenvironmentUsed in a multi -threaded environment Used in a single -threaded \r\nenvironment\r\nSlow Slower than StringBuilder but faster than \r\nStringFaster than StringBuffer\r\nString var =“Java”; \r\nString var=newString(“Java”); StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Java"); StringBuilder var = new \r\nStringBuilder(“Java");\r\nStrings with Special Characters\r\n•The backslash ( \\) escape character turns special characters into string characters\r\n•System.out.println ("She said, \\"Java is fun! \\"");\r\n•System.out.println ("Path: C: \\\\Program Files \\\\Java");Escape character Result Description\r\n\\' ' Single quote\r\n\\" " Double quote\r\n\\\\ \\ Backslash
251	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-11 23:08:24.6467	--- 2 -  Variables and Loops.pdf ---\nIntroduction to Java \nProgramming\nLecture 2\n\nJava Syntax\n•Every line of code that runs in Java must be inside a class.\n•Class name should always start with an uppercase.\n\nThe main Method\n•public static void main(String[] args )\n•Every Java program execution starts with the main method.\n•A mandatory part of every Java program\nPrinting statement\n•System.out.println ("Welcome to Java!");\n•We use the println () method to print a line of text to the screen.\nSystem ---> built -in Java class \nout ---> object\nprintln () ---> method to print a line of text\nJava comments\n•Comments can be used to explain Java code, and to make it more readable.\n•The compiler does not compile the comments.\n•Java comments are of two types : \nSingle line comment\nMulti line comment\nDocumentation comments\nJava comments\n•Single -line comment\n// This is a single line comment\n•Multi -line comment\n/* The is a multi line comment\nused to add comment on multiple lines. */\n•Documentation comments\n/** \n*This is a \n*Documentation comment, used for\n*Documentation of the source code \n*/\nJava Variables\n•Variables are containers for storing data.\n•The general rules for naming variables are:\nCan contain letters, digits, underscores, and dollar signs\nMust begin with a letter, $ or _\nShould start with a lowercase letter, and cannot contain whitespace\nCannot use reserved words (such as int or boolean )\nNames are case -sensitive (" myNum " and " mynum " are different variables)\nDeclaring Variables\n•Syntax:\n<data_type > <variableName > = <value>;\n•Example\nString name = "Leena";\nint age = 27;\nDeclaring Variables\n•You can also declare a variable without assigning the value, and assign the value later:\nint age;\nage = 27;\nSystem.out.println (age);//27\n•Updating values:\nIf you assign a new value to an existing variable, it will overwrite the previous value\nage=28;\nSystem.out.println (age);//28\nMultiple variables in one line\n•To declare more than one variable of the same type, you can use a comma -separated list:\n•Instead of writing:\nint a = 2;\nint b = 9;\nint c = 5;\n•You can simply write:\nint a = 2, b = 9, c = 5;\nFinal keyword\n•When you do not want a variable's value to change, use the final keyword.\n•A variable declared with final becomes a constant, which means unchangeable and read -only:\nfinal int myNum = 7;\nmyNum = 8;  // Error: cannot assign a value to final variable ' myNum '\nData Types\n•Data types are divided into two groups:\nPrimitive data types (built -in)\nNon -primitive data types (reference types)\n•Primitive data types -byte, short, int, long, float, double, boolean , char \n•Non -primitive data types –String, Array, Class, Interface, and Objects\nData Types\n\nActivity\n1. Write a Java statement to declare an integer variable named age and assign the value 20 to it.\n2. How do you declare a double variable named salary with the value 35000.50 in Java?\n3. Write a Java statement to declare a boolean variable named isStudent and assign it the value \ntrue.\n4. How would you declare a character variable named grade and assign the value 'A' in Java?\n5. Write a Java statement to declare a String variable named name with the value "Ram".\nFind out the difference between \nprimitive and non -primitive data types\nPrimitive and non -primitive data types\nPrimitive Non -primitive\nBasic, built -in data types Derived, complex data types\nStores actual value in the memory Stores reference to the object\nFixed Not fixed\nTypically stored in stack memory Reference is in stack, object is in heap memory\nStarts with lowercase letter Starts with uppercase letter\nOperators in Java\n•Java divides the operators into the following groups:\nArithmetic operators (+, -, *, /, %)\nAssignment operators (=, +=, -=, etc.)\nRelational / Comparison operators (==, !=, >, <)\nLogical operators (&&, ||, !)\nConcatenation operator (+ for Strings)\nOperators in Java\n•Arithmetic Operators -To perform common mathematical operations.\n•Assignment Operators -To assign values to variables.\n•Comparison Operators -To compare two values (or variables) and the return value of a comparison \nis either true or false. \n•Logical Operators -To determine the logic between variables or values.\nOperators in Java\n•Concatenation operator\nTo combine both text and a variable\nTo add a variable to another variable\nTo combine two strings, we use concatenation operator\n•Example 1\nString name = "Ananth";\nSystem.out.println ("Hello " + name);\n•Example 2\nString firstName = "John ";\nString lastName = "Doe";\nString fullName = firstName + lastName ;\nSystem.out.println (fullName ); //John Doe\nOperators in Java\n•For numeric values, the ‘+’ character works as a mathematical operator\nint x = 2;\nint y = 9;\nSystem.out.println (x + y); //11\nActivity\nQ1.What will be the output of the following code?\nint x = 10;\nint y = 3;\nSystem.out.println (x / y);\nSystem.out.println (x % y);\nQ2.What does the following print on the screen?\nint a = 5, b = 8;\nSystem.out.println (a > b);\nSystem.out.println (a != b);\nActivity\nQ3.What will be the output following Java code segment?\nboolean p = true, q = false;\nSystem.out.println (p && q);\nSystem.out.println (p || q);\nSystem.out.println (!p);\nQ4. What will be the value of variable `num` after the code runs?\nint num = 10;\nnum += 5;\nnum *= 2;\nSystem.out.println (num);\nActivity\nQ5. What will be the result of:\nint x = 5;\nSystem.out.println (x++);\nSystem.out.println (++x);\nControl structures in Java\n•The if Statement\nto specify a block of Java code to be executed if a condition is true.\n•The condition inside the if statement must result in a boolean value\nif (condition) {\n// code to be executed \n}\n\nControl structures in Java\n•The if else Statement\nwhen the condition is true if block will be executed, if condition is not true else block will be \nexecuted\nif (condition) {\n// code to be executed if the condition is true\n} else {\n// code to be executed if the condition is false\n}\n•Short -hand if else, which is known as the ternary operator\nvariable = (condition) ? expressionTrue :  expressionFalse ;\n\nControl structures in Java\nThe else if ladder\nIf we want to test more than one condition, \nwe use else if ladder.\nif (condition1) {\n// executed if condition1 is true\n} else if (condition2) {\n// executed if the condition1 is false and condition2 is true\n} else {\n// executed if the condition1 is false and condition2 is false\n}\n\nControl structures in Java\nSwitch Statements\nIt is an alternative to an if-else-if ladder\nswitch(expression) {\ncase x:\n// code block\nbreak;\ncase y:\n// code block\nbreak;\ndefault:\n// code block\n}\n\nControl structures in Java\nHow switch statements works?\n•The switch expression is evaluated once.\n•The result is compared with each case value.\n•If there is a match, the matching block of code runs.\n•The break statement stops the switch after the matching case has run.\n•The default statement runs if there is no match.\nLoops\nLoops can execute a block of code as long as a specified condition is reached.\nWhile Loop:\nloops through a block of code as long as a specified condition is true\nwhile (condition) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\n\nLoops\nDo/While Loop:\nThis loop will execute the code block once, before checking if the condition is true. Then it will \nrepeat the loop as long as the condition is true.\ndo {\n// code block to be executed\n}\nwhile (condition);\n\nLoops\nFor Loop:\nWhen you know exactly how many times you want to loop through a block of code, use the for \nloop\nfor (statement 1; statement 2; statement 3) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\nStatement 1 is executed (one time) before the execution of the code block.\nStatement 2 defines the condition for executing the code block.\nStatement 3 is executed (every time) after the code block has been executed.\n\nLoops\nFor-Each loop:\nused to loop through elements in an array\nfor (type variableName : arrayName ) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\n\nActivity\nQ1. Consider the following code snippet. What will be printed on the console?\nint x = 10;\nif (x > 5) {\nSystem.out.println ("A");\n}\nSystem.out.println ("B");\nQ2. Suppose the variable y is initialized as below, what will be the output?\nint y = 8;\nif (y % 2 == 0) {\nSystem.out.println ("Even");\n} else {\nSystem.out.println ("Odd");\n}\nActivity\nQ3. A student’s grade is determined by the following code:\nint marks = 75;\nif (marks >= 90) {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade A");\n} else if (marks >= 60) {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade B");\n} else {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade C");\n}\nWhat grade will be printed on the screen?\nActivity\nQ4. Consider the switch statement below\nint day = 3;\nswitch(day) {\ncase 1: System.out.println ("Monday"); break;\ncase 2: System.out.println ("Tuesday"); break;\ncase 3: System.out.println ("Wednesday"); break;\ndefault: System.out.println ("Other day");\n}\nWhat will be the output?\nActivity\nQ5. How many times will "Hello" be printed?\nfor (int i= 0; i< 5; i++) {\nSystem.out.println ("Hello");\n}\nSummary \n✓Java program structure → everything inside a class\n✓The main() method is the entry point of execution\n✓Printing output with System.out.println ()\n✓Comments: single -line (//) and multi -line (/*...*/)\n✓Variables: rules for naming, declaring, updating values\n✓final keyword → constants (unchangeable values)\n✓Data Types: Primitive (int, double, char, boolean , etc.) and Non -primitive (String, Arrays, Classes, \nObjects)\n✓Operators: Arithmetic, Assignment, Comparison, Logical, Concatenation\n✓Control structures: if, if -else, if -else-if, switch\n✓Loops: while, do -while, for, for -each
252	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-11 23:45:02.522595	--- 4 - Methods.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 4\n\nOutline\n•Instance members\n•Static members\n•Method signature\n•Method overloading\n•Constructor overloading\n•Modifiers\nInstance members\n•The attributes and methods that belong to an object (not the class itself) are called instance \nmembers.\n•Instance members are:\nInstance variables (Attributes): variables declared inside a class but outside methods. Each object \ngets its own copy.\nInstance methods: methods that operate on instance variables and require an object to be \ncalled.\n•In the given  example, name and age are \ninstance variables, and displayInfo () is an \ninstance method. \n•Each object (s1, s2) gets its own copy of the \ninstance variables.\n\nWhat are Static Members?\n•Static members are: Static Variables and Static Methods\n•Static variables and static methods belong to the class , not to objects.\n•Only one copy of a static variable exists and shared among all objects.\n•Can be accessed without creating an object.\nStatic Variables\n•Declared with the static keyword.\n•Shared across all objects of the class.\n•Example: static int x =20;\nStatic Methods\n•Declared with the static keyword.\n•Can be called without creating objects.\n•A static method can only access static variables and static methods directly.\n•Cannot access instance variables/ instance methods.\nDifference between static variables and \ninstance variables \nStatic variable Vs Instance variable\nStatic variable / Class variable Instance variable\nCommon to all objects of a class, if any changes are \nmade to these variables through object, it will reflect in \nother objects as well.Every object will have its own copy of instance \nvariables; hence changes made to these variables \nthrough one object will not reflect in another object.\nStatic variables are declared with keyword static Instance variables are declared without static keyword.\nStatic variables can be used through either class name \nor object reference.Instance variables can be used only via object \nreference.\nDifference between static methods and \ninstance methods \nStatic Method Vs Instance Method\nStatic method Instance method\nCreated using the static keyword and retrieved without \ncreating an object.Requires an object of its class to be invoked.\nAccess only static variables and methods. Can access both static and instance members.\nCannot use this keyword within static methods. Can use this keyword to refer to the current object.\nMethod signature\n•The method signature is the part of the method declaration that uniquely identifies the method .\n•In Java, a method signature consists of two primary components:\nMethod name\nParameter list \n•Example:\ncalculation( int num1, int num2 ) \nadd( double num1, double num2 )\nWhy is Method Signature Important?\n•Used by the compiler and JVM to identify which method to call.\n•Allows method overloading (multiple methods with same name but different parameters).\n•Prevents conflicts in class design.\nMethod overloading\n•Method Overloading allows a class to have multiple methods with the same name, but with \ndifferent parameter lists.\n•It increases code readability and reusability.\n•The compiler decides which method to call (based on arguments)\n•Method overloading in Java is also known as Compile -time Polymorphism , Static Polymorphism, or \nEarly binding, because the decision about which method to call is made at compile time.\nMethod overloading\n•Rules of Method Overloading:\nMethods must have the same name.\nMust differ in the number of parameters, types of parameters, or order of parameters.\nReturn type does not matter for overloading \nConstructor overloading\n•Constructor Overloading means defining multiple constructors in the same class with the same \nname (class name) but different parameter lists.\n•This allows you to create objects with varying initial states based on what data is available when \nthe object is instantiated.\n•The compiler chooses the constructor based on the arguments passed. \nKey Features (Constructor Overloading) \n•Same constructor name but different parameter combinations\n•Compile -time polymorphism in Java\n•Improved code readability and reusability\nModifiers\n•Modifiers are keywords in Java that change the behavior of variables, methods, or classes.\n•We divide modifiers into two groups:\nAccess Modifiers -controls the access level\nNon -Access Modifiers -do not control access level, but provides other functionality\nAccess Modifiers \n•Access modifiers are essential tools that define how the members of a class, like variables, \nmethods, and even the class itself, can be accessed from other parts of our program. \n•Access modifiers define who can access a class, method, or variable.\n•For classes , you can use either public or default\npublic -The class is accessible by any other class\ndefault -The class is only accessible by classes in the same package. This is used when you don't \nspecify a modifier. \nAccess Modifiers \n•For attributes, methods and constructors , you can use the one of the following: public, private, \ndefault, protected\npublic -The code is accessible for all classes\nprivate -The code is only accessible within the declared class\ndefault -The code is only accessible in the same package. This is used when you don't specify a \nmodifier.\nprotected -The code is accessible in the same package and subclasses. \nThe public access modifier\n•The public access modifier is specified using the keyword public. \n•The public access modifier has the widest scope among all other access modifiers.\n•Classes, methods, or data members that are declared as public are accessible from everywhere in \nthe program. \n•There is no restriction on the scope of public data members.\npublic class Student {\npublic String name;   // accessible from any class\n}\nThe private access modifier\n•The private access modifier is specified using the keyword private. \n•The methods or data members declared as private are accessible only within the class in which \nthey are declared and not visible outside the class.\nclass Student {\nprivate int age;  // accessible only inside Student class\nprivate void showAge () {\nSystem.out.println ("Age: " + age);\n}\n}\nThe protected access modifier\n•The protected access modifier is specified using the keyword protected.\n•The methods or data members declared as protected are accessible within the same package or \nsubclasses in different packages.\nclass Person {\nprotected String name; // accessible in subclasses\n}\nclass Student extends Person {\nvoid display() {\nSystem.out.println ("Name: " + name); \n}\n}\nThe default access modifier\n•When no access modifier is specified for a class, method, or data member, it is said to have the \ndefault access modifier by default. \n•Accessible only within the same package.\n•Not accessible from outside the package.\nclass Student {\nString university;  // default access\n}\nSummary \n✓Instance Members\nAttributes (instance variables) → each object gets its own copy.\nInstance methods → require an object to be called.\n✓Static Members\nBelong to the class, not objects.\nOnly one copy exists, shared among all objects.\nCan be accessed without creating an object.\n✓Method Signature\nDefined by: Method name + Parameter list.\nReturn type is not part of the signature.\nUsed by compiler to decide which method to call (important for overloading).\nSummary \n✓Method Overloading\nSame method name, different parameter lists.\nImproves readability and reusability.\nDecided at compile -time.\n✓Constructor Overloading\nSame class name, multiple constructors with different parameter lists.\nAllows flexible object creation.\nFollows rules: must differ in number, type, or order of parameters.\n✓Modifiers\nAccess Modifiers: control visibility.\nNon -Access Modifiers: provide other functionality.
253	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-11 23:45:41.726455	--- 7 -  String class.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 7\n\nOutline\n•Introduction to String class\n•How to Create Java Strings?\n•How Strings are Stored in Memory\n•Java String Methods\n•String Immutability\n•Differences between StringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  in Java\n•Strings with Special Characters\nIntroduction to String class\n•Represents a sequence of characters . \n•A Java String is an ordered, immutable sequence of characters. \n•Immutability means you cannot change a String object after you create it.\n•For example, “hello” or “Java” are strings. \n•String class in java lang package, is used to create string objects.\nHow to Create Java Strings?\n•There are two ways to create a String object:\n•1. Use String Literals \n•This is the most common way to create a String. \n•Java treats text in double quotes as a String literal.\nString s1 = "Welcome";\nString s2 = "Welcome"; // refers to the same object in String Pool\nSystem.out.println (s1 == s2);  \n•2. Use the new Keyword \n•Java String is created by using a keyword “ new ”.\n•Example: String s=new String(“Welcome”);  \nString s3 = new String("Welcome");\nString s4 = new String("Welcome");\nSystem.out.println (s3 == s4); \nHow Strings are Stored in Memory\nString literal\n•Whenever a String Object is created as a literal, the object will be created in the String constant \npool. \n•The string constant pool is present in the heap memory.\n•Example 1: Using String literals to assigning char sequence value.\nString str1 = "Hello";\n•Example 2: When we initialize the same char sequence using string literals.\nString str1 = "Hello";\nString str2 = "Hello";\n•str2 will refer the same object "Hello" in the String constant pool, it will not be created again the \nSting constant pool (Two different references but same object).\n•It means, Java stores String literals in the String Pool. If you create the same String literal twice, \nJava points both variables to the same object in the pool.\nUsing new Keyword\n•The string can also be declared using a new keyword (dynamically allocated). \n•In case of String are dynamically allocated they are assigned a new memory location in the heap . \nThis string will not be added to the String constant pool .\n•Example 1: Using new keyword to assign a char sequence to a String object.\nString str3 = new String(“Hello"); \nString str4 = new String(“Hello");\nJava String Methods\n•Java provides methods to work with Strings. \n•These methods manipulate and analyze text.\n•length()                                               \n•concat () \n•charAt ()\n•equals()\n•equalsIgnoreCase ()\n•indexOf ()\n•substring()\n•replace()\n•toLowerCase ()\n•toUpperCase ()\n•trim()\n•compareTo ()\n•valueOf ()•contains()\n•toCharArray ()\n•isEmpty ()\n•endsWith ()\n•1. Get String Length\nThe length() method returns the number of characters in a String.\n•2. Concatenate Strings\nYou can join two or more Strings. Use the + operator or the concat () method.\n•3. Access Characters\nUse the charAt () method to get a character at a specific index. Indexes start from 0.\n•4. Compare Strings\nThe equals() method compares two Strings. It checks if their content is the same. Use \nequalsIgnoreCase () to ignore case differences.\nDo not use == to compare String content. The == operator checks if two String references point \nto the same object in memory.\n•5. Find Substrings\nThe indexOf () method finds the first occurrence of a substring. It returns the index. If the \nsubstring is not found, it returns -1.\n•6. Extract Substrings\nThe substring() method extracts a portion of a String. You provide start and end indexes.\n•7. Replace Characters or Substrings\nUse replace() to replace characters or substrings.\n•8. Convert Case\nThe toLowerCase () and toUpperCase () methods change the case of a String.\n•9. Trim Whitespace\nThe trim() method removes leading and trailing whitespace.\nActivity\n1.\nString name = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (name.length ()); \n2.\nString s1 = "Hello";\nString s2 = "World";\nSystem.out.println (s1.concat(" " + s2)); \nSystem.out.println (s1 + " " + s2);       \n3.\nString text = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (text.charAt (2)); \n4.\nString a = "Hello";\nString b = "hello";\nSystem.out.println (a.equals (b));            \nSystem.out.println (a.equalsIgnoreCase (b));  \n5.\nString text = "banana";\nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("a"));  \nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("na")); \n6.\nString word = "Programming";\nSystem.out.println (word.substring (0, 4));\n7.\nString name = "car";\nSystem.out.println (name.replace ('c', 'b')); \n8.\nString word = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (word.toUpperCase ()); \nSystem.out.println (word.toLowerCase ()); \n9.\nString s = "  Hello Java  ";\nSystem.out.println (s.trim ()); \n10.\nString s1 = "apple";\nString s2 = "apple";\nSystem.out.println (s1.compareTo(s2));\nString name = "   Java Programming   ";\nSystem.out.println (name.trim ().substring(0, 4). toUpperCase ());\nString Immutability\nString str = "Java";\nstr.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); \nWhat will be the output? why?\n•Output: Java     //Not "Java Programming"\n•Because concat () creates a new String object, it doesn’t modify the original.\n•To store the new value, assign it back:\nString str = "Java";\nstr = str.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); // Output: Java Programming\n•Unlike other data types in Java, Strings are immutable. \n•It means that Strings are constant, their values cannot be changed after they are created.\n•New String is created whenever we do String manipulation. \n•The original String remains unchanged.\nThis immutability offers benefits:\n1. Thread Safety : Multiple threads can access a String without synchronization problems. One thread \ncannot change a String while another reads it.\n2. Security : Immutability is important for security. When you use Strings for sensitive data like \ndatabase credentials, their unchanging nature prevents unintended modifications.\n3. Performance : The String Pool relies on immutability. This helps save memory and improves \nperformance by reusing existing String objects.\nWhat will be the output?\nString s = “Colombo";\ns.concat (" City");\nSystem.out.println (s); \nStringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(“Colombo");\nsb.append (" City");\nSystem.out.println (sb); \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•As String manipulations are resource consuming, Java provides two utility classes: StringBuffer  and \nStringBuilder.\n•StringBuffer  and StringBuilder are mutable classes . \nExample1:\nStringBuffer  sb = new StringBuffer ("Hello");\nsb.append (" World");\nSystem.out.println (sb); // Hello World\nExample2:\nStringBuilder sb2 = new StringBuilder("Java");\nsb2.append(" Rocks");\nSystem.out.println (sb2); // Java Rocks\nFind out the key difference between \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder classes.\n \nStringBuffer StringBuilder\nOperations are thread -safe and synchronized Not thread -safe are not -synchronized\nUsed when multiple threads are working on the same \nString Used in a single -threaded environment\nPerformance is slower when compared to StringBuilder Performance is faster when compared to StringBuffer\nSyntax: StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Hello”); Syntax: StringBuilder var = new StringBuilder(“Hello”);\nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  \nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer\n•The differences between String, StringBuffer , and StringBuilder are based on the following two \nparameters:\nMutability\nPerformance\nString StringBuffer StringBuilder\nString Pool Heap Heap\nImmutable Mutable Mutable\nNot used in a threaded \nenvironmentUsed in a multi -threaded environment Used in a single -threaded \nenvironment\nSlow Slower than StringBuilder but faster than \nStringFaster than StringBuffer\nString var =“Java”; \nString var=newString(“Java”); StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Java"); StringBuilder var = new \nStringBuilder(“Java");\nStrings with Special Characters\n•The backslash ( \\) escape character turns special characters into string characters\n•System.out.println ("She said, \\"Java is fun! \\"");\n•System.out.println ("Path: C: \\\\Program Files \\\\Java");Escape character Result Description\n\\' ' Single quote\n\\" " Double quote\n\\\\ \\ Backslash
254	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 00:11:25.28709	--- 8 - Arrays.pdf ---\nJava Arrays\nLecture 8\n\nOutline\n•Introduction\n•Key Features\n•Advantages and Disadvantages\n•Types of Array in Java\n•Limitations of Arrays\n•ArrayList\n•Features of ArrayList\n•Array Vs ArrayList\nIntroduction to Arrays\n•An array is a collection of elements of the same data type stored in contiguous memory locations.\n•Why use arrays?\nTo store multiple values in a single variable instead of multiple separate variables.\nExample:\nint marks1 = 85;\nint marks2 = 90;\nint marks3 = 78;\n•Instead, use an array: int[] marks = {85, 90, 78};\nKey Features of Arrays\n•Fixed in size (cannot grow / shrink)\n•Stores elements of same type\n•Accessed by index (starting from 0)\n•Stored in contiguous memory\nAdvantages and Disadvantages\nAdvantages\n•Code Optimization: Store and process data efficiently\n•Random Access: Direct access using index\nDisadvantages\n•Fixed Size: Cannot resize at runtime\n•Same Type: Cannot mix data types\nTypes of Array in java\n•There are two types of array:\n1. Single Dimensional Array\n2. Multidimensional Array\nSingle Dimensional Array\n\nSingle Dimensional Array\n•Declaration: int[] numbers; or  int []numbers; or  int numbers[];\n•Instantiation (Memory Allocation): numbers = new int[5];  \n•Assigning Values Individually\nnumbers[0] = 10;\nnumbers[1] = 20;\nnumbers[2] = 30;\nnumbers[3] = 40;\nnumbers[4] = 50;\n•Declaration and Initialization\nint[] numbers = new int[] {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};\n•shortcut syntax:\nint[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};\nNote: In Java, when using new, you either:\n•Use new int[5] to create an empty array with 5 slots , and then fill them later\n•Or use new int[] {10, 20, 30, 40, 50} (without specifying the number of elements) to create the \narray and assign values at the same time.\n•The shortcut syntax is most often used when the values are known at the start. \n•You cannot write new int[5] {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};\n•Accessing Array Elements\nUse the index position:\nSystem.out.println (numbers[0]);\n•Iterating Through Array\nUsing for Loop:\nint[] nums  = {10, 20, 30, 40};\nfor (int i = 0; i < nums.length ; i++) {\n    System.out.println (nums [i]);\n}\n•Iterating Through Array\nUsing for -each Loop:\nfor (int n : nums ) {\n    System.out.println (n);\n}\n•Array Length Property\nSystem.out.println (nums.length ); \nExample:\npublic class Main{    \n public static void main(String args[]){    \n    int a[]=new int[5];  \n    a[0]=10;\n    a[1]=20;    \n    a[2]=30;    \n    a[3]=40;    \n    a[4]=50;    \n    for(int i=0;i< a.length;i ++){\n        System.out.println (a[i]);    \n    }  \n }  \n} \nWrite a Java program to get the average \nmarks of the below given array:\nint[] marks = {85, 90, 78, 92, 88};\nAnswer:\npublic class AverageMarks  {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        int[] marks = {85, 90, 78, 92, 88};\n        int sum = 0;\n        for (int m : marks)\n            sum += m;\n        double avg = (double) sum / marks.length ;\n        System.out.println ("Average Marks: " + avg);\n    }\n}\nMultidimensional Arrays\n\nMultidimensional Arrays\n•A multidimensional array in Java is an array of arrays where each element can be an array itself. \n•It is useful for storing data in row and column format.\n•2D Array Declaration:\nint[][] matrix;  \n•Instantiation\nmatrix = new int[2][3];\n•Assigning Values Individually\narr[0][0]=1;  \narr[0][1]=2;  \narr[0][2]=3;  \narr[1][0]=4;  \narr[1][1]=5;  \narr[1][2]=6;  \n•Declaration and Initialization\nint[][] matrix = {\n    {1, 2, 3},\n    {4, 5, 6}\n};\n•Access Elements:\nSystem.out.println (matrix[1][2]); \n•Iterating Through Arrays\nNested Loops to Display 2D Array:\nfor (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {\n    for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {\n        System.out.print (matrix[ i][j] + " ");\n    }\n    System.out.println ();\n}\nLimitations of Arrays\n•Fixed size (cannot grow dynamically)\n•Manual index handling\n•No built -in methods to add, remove, or search\n•Can only hold elements of one type\n•Example:\npublic class Main {    \n    public static void main(String args[]) {    \n        int arr[][] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}, {7, 8, 9}}; // 3x3 matrix    \n        // Printing the 2D array    \n        for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {    \n            for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {    \n                System.out.print (arr[i][j] + " ");    \n            }    \n            System.out.println ();    \n        }    \n    }    \n} \nWhat is ArrayList ?\n•ArrayList  in Java is a dynamic array implementation that belongs to the Java Collections \nFramework. \n•It grows automatically as elements are added and shrinks when removed.\n•ArrayLists  come from the java.util  package and are quite commonly used for their ease of use and \nflexibility.\n•It inherits the AbstractList  class and implements List interface.\nFeatures of ArrayList\n•Dynamic in size\n•Can hold objects only (not primitive types directly)\n•Can add, remove, and access elements easily\n•Found in java.util  package\n•Creating an ArrayList : ArrayList <String> names = new ArrayList <String>();\n•Adding Elements\nnames.add ("Kamal");\nnames.add ("Nimal");\nnames.add ("Saman");\n•Accessing Elements\nSystem.out.println (names.get (0)); // prints Kamal\n•Iterating ArrayList\nfor (String n : names) {\n    System.out.println (n);\n}\n•Removing Elements\nnames.remove ("Nimal");       // remove by value\nnames.remove (1);             // remove by index\n•Getting the Size\nSystem.out.println (names.size ()); // prints number of elements\n•Modifying Elements\nnames.set (0, "Amal"); // changes Kamal → Amal\n•Clearing the ArrayList\nnames.clear ();\nExample:\nimport java.util .*;\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        ArrayList <String> names = new ArrayList <String>();\n        names.add ("Kamal");\n        names.add ("Nimal");\n        names.add ("Saman");\n        System.out.println (names.get (0)); // Kamal\n        names.set (0, "Amal"); // Modify element\n        names.remove ("Nimal"); // Remove element\n        System.out.println ("Size: " + names.size ()); // Size: 2\n        System.out.println (names ); // [Amal, Saman]\n    }\n}\nDifference Between Array and ArrayList\nFeature  Array ArrayList\nSize Fixed  Dynamic\nType Can hold primitives Holds objects only\nPerformance Fast Slightly slower\nFlexibility Limited High (add/remove easily)\nActivity\n•1. Which of the following statements is true regarding Java arrays?\na) Java arrays can dynamically change their size.\nb) Java arrays can store elements of different data types.\nc) Java arrays are always initialized with default values.\nd) Java arrays do not allow duplicate elements.\n•2. What will happen if we try to access an element at an index that is greater than or equal to the \narray's length?\na) The program will crash with a segmentation fault.\nb) The program will return a default value.\nc) The program will throw an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException .\nd) The program will compile but not run.\n•3. Which of the following interfaces does the Java ArrayList  class directly implement?\na) Set\nb) Queue\nc) List\nd) Map\n•4. When an element is removed from an ArrayList , which of the following best describes the impact \non the remaining elements?\na) All elements are rehashed\nb) No impact on remaining elements\nc) Elements after the removed element are shifted left\nd) ArrayList  becomes immutable\n•5. How does Java ArrayList  handle the scenario when its capacity needs to be increased?\na) It throws an OutOfMemoryError\nb) It uses a linked list to accommodate the new elements\nc) It creates a new array with increased capacity and copies elements over\nd) It appends elements to a secondary array\n6. What will be the output?\npublic class TestArray  {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        int[] nums  = {2, 4, 6, 8, 10};\n        System.out.println (nums [nums.length  - 2]);\n    }\n}\na) 6\nb) 8\nc) 10\nd) Compilation error\n7.\npublic class SumArray  {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        int[] numbers = {1, 3, 5, 7};\n        int sum = 0;\n        for (int i = 1; i < numbers.length ; i++) {\n            sum += numbers[ i];\n        }\n        System.out.println (sum);\n    }\n}\nWhat will be printed?\na) 16\nb) 15\nc) 20\nd) 12\n8.\nimport java.util .*;\npublic class TestList  {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        ArrayList <String> list = new ArrayList <>();\n        list.add ("Java");\n        list.add ("Python");\n        list.add ("C++");\n        list.remove (1);\n        list.add ("Go");\n        System.out.println (list);  } }\nWhat is the output?\na) [Java, Python, Go]\nb) [Java, C++, Go]\nc) [Python, C++, Go]\nd) [Java, Go]
