a stores String literals in the String Pool. If you create the same String literal twice, \nJava points both variables to the same object in the pool.\nUsing new Keyword\n•The string can also be declared using a new keyword (dynamically allocated). \n•In case of String are dynamically allocated they are assigned a new memory location in the heap . \nThis string will not be added to the String constant pool .\n•Example 1: Using new keyword to assign a char sequence to a String object.\nString str3 = new String(“Hello"); \nString str4 = new String(“Hello");\nJava String Methods\n•Java provides methods to work with Strings. \n•These methods manipulate and analyze text.\n•length()                                               \n•concat () \n•charAt ()\n•equals()\n•equalsIgnoreCase ()\n•indexOf ()\n•substring()\n•replace()\n•toLowerCase ()\n•toUpperCase ()\n•trim()\n•compareTo ()\n•valueOf ()•contains()\n•toCharArray ()\n•isEmpty ()\n•endsWith ()\n•1. Get String Length\nThe length() method returns the number of characters in a String.\n•2. Concatenate Strings\nYou can join two or more Strings. Use the + operator or the concat () method.\n•3. Access Characters\nUse the charAt () method to get a character at a specific index. Indexes start from 0.\n•4. Compare Strings\nThe equals() method compares two Strings. It checks if their content is the same. Use \nequalsIgnoreCase () to ignore case differences.\nDo not use == to compare String content. The == operator checks if two String references point \nto the same object in memory.\n•5. Find Substrings\nThe indexOf () method finds the first occurrence of a substring. It returns the index. If the \nsubstring is not found, it returns -1.\n•6. Extract Substrings\nThe substring() method extracts a portion of a String. You provide start and end indexes.\n•7. Replace Characters or Substrings\nUse replace() to replace characters or substrings.\n•8. Convert Case\nThe toLowerCase () and toUpperCase () methods change the case of a String.\n•9. Trim Whitespace\nThe trim() method removes leading and trailing whitespace.\nActivity\n1.\nString name = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (name.length ()); \n2.\nString s1 = "Hello";\nString s2 = "World";\nSystem.out.println (s1.concat(" " + s2)); \nSystem.out.println (s1 + " " + s2);       \n3.\nString text = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (text.charAt (2)); \n4.\nString a = "Hello";\nString b = "hello";\nSystem.out.println (a.equals (b));            \nSystem.out.println (a.equalsIgnoreCase (b));  \n5.\nString text = "banana";\nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("a"));  \nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("na")); \n6.\nString word = "Programming";\nSystem.out.println (word.substring (0, 4));\n7.\nString name = "car";\nSystem.out.println (name.replace ('c', 'b')); \n8.\nString word = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (word.toUpperCase ()); \nSystem.out.println (word.toLowerCase ()); \n9.\nString s = "  Hello Java  ";\nSystem.out.println (s.trim ()); \n10.\nString s1 = "apple";\nString s2 = "apple";\nSystem.out.println (s1.compareTo(s2));\nString name = "   Java Programming   ";\nSystem.out.println (name.trim ().substring(0, 4). toUpperCase ());\nString Immutability\nString str = "Java";\nstr.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); \nWhat will be the output? why?\n•Output: Java     //Not "Java Programming"\n•Because concat () creates a new String object, it doesn’t modify the original.\n•To store the new value, assign it back:\nString str = "Java";\nstr = str.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); // Output: Java Programming\n•Unlike other data types in Java, Strings are immutable. \n•It means that Strings are constant, their values cannot be changed after they are created.\n•New String is created whenever we do String manipulation. \n•The original String remains unchanged.\nThis immutability offers benefits:\n1. Thread Safety : Multiple threads can access a String without synchronization problems. One thread \ncannot change a String while another reads it.\n2. Security : Immutability is important for security. When you use Strings for sensitive data like \ndatabase credentials, their unchanging nature prevents unintended modifications.\n3. Performance : The String Pool relies on immutability. This helps save memory and improves \nperformance by reusing existing String objects.\nWhat will be the output?\nString s = “Colombo";\ns.concat (" City");\nSystem.out.println (s); \nStringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(“Colombo");\nsb.append (" City");\nSystem.out.println (sb); \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•As String manipulations are resource consuming, Java provides two utility classes: StringBuffer  and \nStringBuilder.\n•StringBuffer  and StringBuilder are mutable classes . \nExample1:\nStringBuffer  sb = new StringBuffer ("Hello");\nsb.append (" World");\nSystem.out.println (sb); // Hello World\nExample2:\nStringBuilder sb2 = new StringBuilder("Java");\nsb2.append(" Rocks");\nSystem.out.println (sb2); // Java Rocks\nFind out the key difference between \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder classes.\n \nStringBuffer StringBuilder\nOperations are thread -safe and synchronized Not thread -safe are not -synchronized\nUsed when multiple threads are working on the same \nString Used in a single -threaded environment\nPerformance is slower when compared to StringBuilder Performance is faster when compared to StringBuffer\nSyntax: StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Hello”); Syntax: StringBuilder var = new StringBuilder(“Hello”);\nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  \nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer\n•The differences between String, StringBuffer , and StringBuilder are based on the following two \nparameters:\nMutability\nPerformance\nString StringBuffer StringBuilder\nString Pool Heap Heap\nImmutable Mutable Mutable\nNot used in a threaded \nenvironmentUsed in a multi -threaded environment Used in a single -threaded \nenvironment\nSlow Slower than StringBuilder but faster than \nStringFaster than StringBuffer\nString var =“Java”; \nString var=newString(“Java”); StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Java"); StringBuilder var = new \nStringBuilder(“Java");\nStrings with Special Characters\n•The backslash ( \\) escape character turns special characters into string characters\n•System.out.println ("She said, \\"Java is fun! \\"");\n•System.out.println ("Path: C: \\\\Program Files \\\\Java");Escape character Result Description\n\\' ' Single quote\n\\" " Double quote\n\\\\ \\ Backslash
256	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 00:13:52.322795	--- 10 - Threads.pdf ---\nThreads in Java\nLecture 10\n\nOutline\n•What is a Thread?\n•Why Multi -threading?\n•Creating Threads in Java\n•Controlling the Threads\n•Thread Life Cycle\n•Thread Priority\nWhat is a Thread?\n•A thread is a lightweight subprocess and the smallest unit of execution.\n•Has a single flow of control: start → process → end.\n•Java’s main() runs in the main thread (single -threaded by default).\n•Java supports multi -threading: multiple threads run concurrently for : \nbetter performance & responsiveness. \nEfficient resource utilization\nWhy Multi -threading?\n•Better resource utilization \n•Responsive UIs\n•Parallel processing\nHow?\nAlthough only one thread runs at a time  on a single core , the JVM  rapidly switches between threads , \ngiving the illusion  of simultaneous execution (time -slicing).\nThis switch is called thread context switching. \nCreating Threads in Java\n•A thread program is created in the one of the following ways:\n1. Extend the "Thread“ class\n2. Implement the "Runnable“ interface\nExtending the Thread class\n•When extending the class Thread, the steps to be included:\n1. Extending the base class "Thread“\n2. Override the method "run" (All the thread program codes should include the run method)\n3. Create an instance for your class\n4. Call the method start() to instantiate the thread program process\nFormat:\nclass MyThread  extends Thread {\n  public void run(){\n  //Thread code included here\n  }\n}\nclass MainThread {\n  public static void main(){\n  MyThread  obj1 = new MyThread ();\n  obj1.start();\n  }\n}\nActivity\n•Create thread classes ThreadA , ThreadB , ThreadC . Override the method run by printing the \nintegers from 1 to 5. Create objects for each class and execute the method run using the method \nstart.\nImplementing runnable interface\n•Steps to follow:\n1. Declare the class as implementing runnable interface\n2. Implement the method run\n3. Create an instance for the declared class\n4. Create a Thread class instance, that should instantiate by the already created instance\n5. Call the method start() by thread class instance\n•Format\nclass MyThread  implements Runnable {\n  public void run(){\n  // Thread code included here\n  }\n}\nclass MainThread {\n  public static void main(String args[]){\n  MyThread  obj1  = new MyThread ();\n  Thread  thobj  = new Thread( obj1 );\n  thobj.start ();\n  }\n}\nActivity\n•Create a thread implements Runnable interface and override the method run by printing integers \nfrom 1 to 10. Execute the run method.\nControlling the thread\n•Controlling the thread can be done in 2 ways:\n1. Stopping a thread\n2. Blocking a thread\nStopping a thread\n•To stop a thread from running further, we can call the stop()  from the Thread class.\n•This method cause the Dead or Destroy state.\n•A thread move into the dead state will not re -join in the process.\nBlocking a thread\n•A thread can be temporarily block from its running process.\n•This is called blocking a Thread.\n•This will cause a thread to move down to the blocked state.\n•This can be achieved by following methods:\nsleep()\nwait()\nsuspend()\nsleep()  - Block period is in milli seconds.\nOnce the time expires and the thread re-enters to the runnable and subsequently the running state.\nwait() - Block the thread until certain condition occur\nwaiting thread re-enter the runnable state by calling the notify() from Thread class.\nsuspend()  - Block the thread until some errors were correct.\nsuspended thread re-enters the runnable state by calling the resume() from Thread class.\nThread Life Cycle\n•Threads in Java go through several states:\n1. New - Thread is created but not started.\n2. Runnable - Ready to run and waiting for CPU time.\n3. Running - Currently executing.\n4. Blocked or Idle - Temporarily inactive.\n5. Dead or Destroyed - Finished execution or stopped.\nState Transition Diagram of a Thread\n\nNew state\n•When we create a thread object, the thread is born and said to be in the Newborn / New state.\n•Once the thread object is created it is not schedule for running. \n•At this state we can do one of the followings:\n1. Schedule the thread for running using the start()\n2. Kill the thread by calling stop()\nRunnable state\n•The thread is ready to perform the execution and is waiting for the availability of the process.\n•Means thread has joined the queue of threads that are waiting for execution.\n•If all threads have same priority, then they are given the time slots for the execution in first come \nfirst serve manner.\nRunning state\n•The processor has given its time  to a Thread for the execution.\n•The running Thread will continue the execution until it complete its task.\n•Once the task completed then move to the death state.\n•Running thread may relinquishes its own control to another thread by its own, by calling the yield() \nmethod.\n•If the control is given to another thread, then the running thread goes back to the runnable state and \nthe subsequently enters to the running state.\n•Running can be block by the user, using thread blocking methods. Then running thread temporarily \nmoves to the block state.\nBlocked or Idle state\n•Threads are idle at this state. \n•Threads will move back as an active thread , or it can sed to the dead state by calling the \nappropriate thread method.\nDead or Destroyed state\n•Every thread has a life cycle. Once the life ends its automatically move to the dead state and never \nre enter the execution cycle.\n•Sometimes a thread will be sent to the dead state by calling stop() from any thread state.\n•stop() is the only method that can be called from any thread state.\nThread Priority\n•In java each thread is assigned a priority, which affects the execution order of the thread process.\n•The threads have the same priority will given the same treatment by scheduler and they work on \nfirst come first serve manner.\n•Java permits to set priority to a thread by calling the method setPriority ()\nEx:\nThreadobj.setPriority (int Number)\n•The parameter int Number is an integer parameter to set the priority. this can be one of the \nfollowing priority constants, or an integer from 1 -10.\n•MIN_PRIORITY = 1 (Lowest priority)\n•NORM -PRIORITY = 5 (Default priority)\n•MAX_PRIORITY = 10 (Highest priority)
257	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 25 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	25	1	easy	2026-04-12 00:21:59.105384	--- 5 - Core concepts of OOP.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 5\n\nThe four core concepts OOP\n•Encapsulation\n•Inheritance\n•Polymorphism\n•Abstraction\nEncapsulation\n•Encapsulation is a mechanism where you bind your data and code together as a single unit. \n•It also means to hide your data to make it safe from any modification. \n•Can achieve data hiding and controlled access.\n•The best way to understand encapsulation is to look at the example of a medical capsule , where \nthe drug is always safe inside the capsule. \n•Similarly, through encapsulation the methods and variables of a class are well hidden and safe.\n\n•We can achieve encapsulation in Java by:\nDeclaring the variables of a class as private .\nProviding public setter and getter methods to modify and view the variables values.\nAdvantages\n•Data hiding : If there are no getters, we cannot see the data. \n•Immutability : If there are no setters, we can’t change the data it is called as immutability. \n•Data validation : We can only check the value by using setters. This is called as data validation \nInheritance\n•Inheritance is a mechanism in which one class acquires (inherits) the properties and behaviors \n(fields and methods) of another class.\n•Inheritance is the process of creating sub classes from the existing base class . The sub class able to \naccess most of the members(excluding private type members) from its base class and include its \nown members.\n•It promotes code reusability and helps establish a natural parent –child relationship between \nclasses.\n•A child inherits certain characteristics (like eye color, blood group) from parents. Similarly, in Java, \nthere are two classes:\n1. Parent class ( Super class or Base class)\n2. Child class (Sub class or Derived class )\n•A class which inherits the properties is known as Child Class whereas a class whose properties are \ninherited is known as Parent class.\n•Inheritance is further classified into 4 types:\nSingle Inheritance\nMultilevel Inheritance\nHierarchical Inheritance\nMultiple inheritance (Not supported by Java)\nSingle Inheritance\n•In single inheritance, one class inherits the properties and behavior of another. \n•It enables a derived class to inherit the properties and behavior from a single parent class.\n•Let’s see the syntax for single inheritance:\nclass A\n{\n}\nclass B extends A {\n}\nMultilevel Inheritance\n•Having more than one parent class but at different levels , such type of inheritance is called \nMultilevel Inheritance.\n•Let’s see the syntax for multilevel inheritance in Java:\nclass A{\n}\nclass B extends A{\n}\nclass C extends B{\n}\nHierarchical Inheritance\n•When a class has more than one child classes (sub classes), then such kind of inheritance is known as \nhierarchical inheritance.\n•Let’s see the syntax for hierarchical inheritance in Java:\nclass A{\n}\nclass B extends A{\n}\nclass C extends A{\n}\nSingle, Multilevel, and Hierarchical    \nInheritances\n•The Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical Inheritances maintain " is a" relationship between the base class \nand the sub class.\n•This relation enable a subclass to legally access the members from its base class.\n•The term " is a" refers to " extends " keyword in Java.\n•"extends" keyword creates a legal relation between base and sub class.\n•That's why Java accepts Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical Inheritances.\nMultiple inheritance\n•Multiple inheritance is not supported by Java as it because it can lead to ambiguity problems (e.g., \nthe diamond problem).\n•This type of inheritance can only be achieved by the interfaces .\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism means taking many forms , where ‘poly’ means many and ‘morph’ means forms . \n•It is the ability of a variable, function or object to take on multiple forms. \n•In other words, polymorphism allows you define one interface or method and have multiple \nimplementations.\nLet’s consider this real -world scenario of \nmusical instruments!\n•Weknow that there aredifferent types ofinstruments such as\nGuitar, Piano, and Drum .Imagine there isaparent class called\nInstrument, and ithas three child classes :Guitar, Piano, and\nDrum .The parent class contains amethod playSound (),which is\ninherited byallchild classes .Now, asweallknow, aGuitar\nproduces sound differently compared toaPiano oraDrum .The\nGuitar willstrum strings, thePiano willplay keys, and theDrum\nwill create beats .Although allthree classes inherit the same\nmethod name playSound (),their implementation iscompletely\ndifferent depending onthetype ofinstrument .\n•The point ofthis discussion isthat asingle method name can\ntake multiple forms .The same method (playSound ())behaves\ndifferently depending onwhich object calls it.\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism in Java is of two types:\nCompile time polymorphism\nRun time polymorphism\nCompile time polymorphism\n•Compile -time polymorphism happens when multiple methods in the same class share the same \nname but differ in their parameter list (number of parameters or type of parameters).\n•The decision of which method to call is made by the compiler at compile time, not at runtime.\nRun time polymorphism\n•Runtime polymorphism happens when a subclass provides its own implementation of a method \nthat is already defined in its superclass.\n•Which version of the method gets executed is determined at runtime based on the object being \nreferred to, not the reference type.\nAbstraction\n•Abstraction is the process of hiding the internal implementation details and showing only the \nessential features to the user.\n•You can achieve abstraction in two ways:\nAbstract Class\nInterface\nSummary \n✓Encapsulation → Bundling data (attributes) and methods together\n✓Inheritance → Child class inherits properties & behaviors from parent class; promotes code reuse.\nTypes: Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical (Multiple via interfaces only).\n✓Polymorphism → One name, many forms.\nCompile -time → Method Overloading.\nRuntime → Method Overriding.\n✓Abstraction → Hiding internal details, showing only essential features.\nAchieved using abstract classes and interfaces.\n✓Real -world examples:\nEncapsulation → Medical capsule.\nInheritance → Child inherits eye color from parents.\nPolymorphism → Different instruments playing sound differently.
