and have multiple \nimplementations.\nLet’s consider this real -world scenario of \nmusical instruments!\n•Weknow that there aredifferent types ofinstruments such as\nGuitar, Piano, and Drum .Imagine there isaparent class called\nInstrument, and ithas three child classes :Guitar, Piano, and\nDrum .The parent class contains amethod playSound (),which is\ninherited byallchild classes .Now, asweallknow, aGuitar\nproduces sound differently compared toaPiano oraDrum .The\nGuitar willstrum strings, thePiano willplay keys, and theDrum\nwill create beats .Although allthree classes inherit the same\nmethod name playSound (),their implementation iscompletely\ndifferent depending onthetype ofinstrument .\n•The point ofthis discussion isthat asingle method name can\ntake multiple forms .The same method (playSound ())behaves\ndifferently depending onwhich object calls it.\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism in Java is of two types:\nCompile time polymorphism\nRun time polymorphism\nCompile time polymorphism\n•Compile -time polymorphism happens when multiple methods in the same class share the same \nname but differ in their parameter list (number of parameters or type of parameters).\n•The decision of which method to call is made by the compiler at compile time, not at runtime.\nRun time polymorphism\n•Runtime polymorphism happens when a subclass provides its own implementation of a method \nthat is already defined in its superclass.\n•Which version of the method gets executed is determined at runtime based on the object being \nreferred to, not the reference type.\nAbstraction\n•Abstraction is the process of hiding the internal implementation details and showing only the \nessential features to the user.\n•You can achieve abstraction in two ways:\nAbstract Class\nInterface\nSummary \n✓Encapsulation → Bundling data (attributes) and methods together\n✓Inheritance → Child class inherits properties & behaviors from parent class; promotes code reuse.\nTypes: Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical (Multiple via interfaces only).\n✓Polymorphism → One name, many forms.\nCompile -time → Method Overloading.\nRuntime → Method Overriding.\n✓Abstraction → Hiding internal details, showing only essential features.\nAchieved using abstract classes and interfaces.\n✓Real -world examples:\nEncapsulation → Medical capsule.\nInheritance → Child inherits eye color from parents.\nPolymorphism → Different instruments playing sound differently.
259	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 00:36:51.249045	--- 1 - Intro to Java.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nObject -Oriented \nProgramming \nLecture 1\nMs. Dinusha Chandrakumaran\nBSc. (Hons) in Information Technology\nLearning objectives & outcomes\n•Learning Objectives: On successful completion of this module, students will be able to use object -\noriented programming principles to develop software solutions. \n•At the completion of this module, learners should be able to:\n➢Explain thebasics ofobject -oriented programming .\n➢Explain theprogramming notions :arrays, handling strings, and handling input/outputs .\n➢Explain thebest practices inobject -oriented programming byevaluating Java programs .\n➢Apply Java event handling, Java database connectivity and unit testing forsoftware development .\n➢Design and develop asmall -scale software solution forareal-world problem using object -oriented\nprogramming .\nSyllabus outline\n•Introduction to Java programming \n•Fundamentals of object -oriented programming \n•Arrays \n•Strings \n•Input and output Handling \n•Essentials of Exceptions and Threads \n•Graphical User Interface (GUI) and event handling \n•Introduction to Java database connectivity \n•Unit testing and debugging \n•Best practices in object -oriented programming \nGrading\n•Continuous Assessments -40% \n•Final Examination -60% \nIntroduction to Java \nProgramming\nUnit 01\n\nWhat is Java?\nJava is:\n•high -level\n•object -oriented \n•Secure\nprogramming language\nDeveloped by Sun Microsystems (which is now a subsidiary of Oracle) in the year 1995.\nA Brief History of Java\n•James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton  small team of sun engineers initiated the Java \nlanguage project in June 1991\n•Initially it was designed for small, embedded systems in electronic appliances like set -top boxes.\n•Firstly, it was called " Greentalk " by James Gosling\n•After that, it was called Oak\n\nA Brief History …\n•In 1995, Oak was renamed as "Java" because it was already a trademark by Oak Technologies.\n•Java is an island in Indonesia where the first coffee was produced (called Java coffee). \n•Java name was chosen by James Gosling while having a cup of coffee nearby his office.\n•Initially developed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems (which is now a subsidiary of Oracle \nCorporation) and released in 1995.\nKey Features of Java\n•Simple\n•Object -Oriented\n•Portable & Platform Independent\n•Multithreaded\n•Secured\nFind out the other key features of Java (Self -study)\nFind out the key difference between \nJava and C\nJava vs C –Key Differences\nJava C\nObject -Oriented language Procedural Programming Language\nHigh -level language Low-level language\nDoes not support pointers Supports pointers\nPortable Not portable\nplatform independent Platform dependent\nSupports OOPS concept Does not support OOPS concept\nHow Java Works\n(Execution \nProcess)\nJava programs are executed in 2 stage:\n•1st stage, the Java compiler convert the \nsource code into byte code\n•2nd stage, Java interpreter convert byte code \ninto real machine code\n\nJVM, JRE, JDK –What’s the Difference?\nJVM (Java Virtual Machine)\n•It is called a virtual machine because it doesn't physically exist. \n•It provides a runtime environment in which Java bytecode can be executed.\nThe JVM performs the following main tasks:\n•Loads code\n•Verifies code\n•Executes code\n•Provides runtime environment\nJVM, JRE, JDK –What’s the Difference?\nJRE(Java Runtime Environment)\n•Java Runtime Environment is a set of software tools that are used for developing Java applications. \n•It physically exists. \n•It is used to provide the runtime environment. It is the implementation of JVM. \n•It contains a set of libraries + other files that the JVM uses at runtime.\nJVM, JRE, JDK –What’s the Difference?\nJDK(Java Development Kit)\n•The Java Development Kit (JDK) is a software development environment that is used to develop \nJava applications. \n•It physically exists. \n•It contains JRE + development tools.\nJVM, JRE, JDK\n\nGetting started\n•Java development typically requires the Java Development Kit (JDK), which includes the Java \ncompiler and other essential tools. \n•You can download the JDK from the official Oracle website and follow the installation instructions \nfor your operating system.\n•Once we have the JDK installed, you can use a text editor or an Integrated Development \nEnvironment (IDE) like IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, or NetBeans to write and run your Java code. \n•For executing any Java program:\nInstall the JDK \nSet path of the jdk/bin directory\nCreate the Java program.\nCompile and run the Java program.\nLet’s Code! Hello World\nSave your file as Main.java\npublic class Main {\npublic static void main(String[] args) {\nSystem.out.println ("Hello World");\n}\n}\nTo compile: javac Main.java\nTo execute: java Main\nOutput: Hello World\n\nWrite a Java program to print your name \non the screen\nPractice Questions\n1. Who is known as the father of Java programming language?\na. James Gosling\nb. Bjarne Stroustrup\nc.Dennis Ritchie\nd. Guido van Rossum\n2. Which feature of Java makes it portable?\na. Dynamic binding\nb. Bytecode\nc.Reflection\nd. Serialization\nPractice Questions\n3. Which component of the Java ecosystem is responsible for providing libraries, Java Virtual Machine \n(JVM), and other components to run applications written in Java?\na. JDK\nb. JRE\nc.JVM\nd. JCL\n4. What role does the JVM play in the Java execution process?\na. It provides a development environment for Java programmers.\nb. It converts Java source code into bytecode.\nc.It interprets and executes Java bytecode.\nd. It manages memory allocation for the operating system.\nPractice Questions\n5. Which of the following is the correct way to compile a Java program named Example.java?\njava Example.java\njavac Example\njavac Example.java\njava Example\nSummary \n✓What Java is and why it’s important\n✓History: From Greentalk to Java\n✓Features: Simple, OOP , portable, secure\n✓Java vs C\n✓How Java runs: Compilation → Bytecode → JVM\n✓JVM, JRE, JDK\n✓Wrote and ran our first program!\nQ & A ?\nThank you!
260	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 00:42:40.680722	--- 7 -  String class.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 7\n\nOutline\n•Introduction to String class\n•How to Create Java Strings?\n•How Strings are Stored in Memory\n•Java String Methods\n•String Immutability\n•Differences between StringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  in Java\n•Strings with Special Characters\nIntroduction to String class\n•Represents a sequence of characters . \n•A Java String is an ordered, immutable sequence of characters. \n•Immutability means you cannot change a String object after you create it.\n•For example, “hello” or “Java” are strings. \n•String class in java lang package, is used to create string objects.\nHow to Create Java Strings?\n•There are two ways to create a String object:\n•1. Use String Literals \n•This is the most common way to create a String. \n•Java treats text in double quotes as a String literal.\nString s1 = "Welcome";\nString s2 = "Welcome"; // refers to the same object in String Pool\nSystem.out.println (s1 == s2);  \n•2. Use the new Keyword \n•Java String is created by using a keyword “ new ”.\n•Example: String s=new String(“Welcome”);  \nString s3 = new String("Welcome");\nString s4 = new String("Welcome");\nSystem.out.println (s3 == s4); \nHow Strings are Stored in Memory\nString literal\n•Whenever a String Object is created as a literal, the object will be created in the String constant \npool. \n•The string constant pool is present in the heap memory.\n•Example 1: Using String literals to assigning char sequence value.\nString str1 = "Hello";\n•Example 2: When we initialize the same char sequence using string literals.\nString str1 = "Hello";\nString str2 = "Hello";\n•str2 will refer the same object "Hello" in the String constant pool, it will not be created again the \nSting constant pool (Two different references but same object).\n•It means, Java stores String literals in the String Pool. If you create the same String literal twice, \nJava points both variables to the same object in the pool.\nUsing new Keyword\n•The string can also be declared using a new keyword (dynamically allocated). \n•In case of String are dynamically allocated they are assigned a new memory location in the heap . \nThis string will not be added to the String constant pool .\n•Example 1: Using new keyword to assign a char sequence to a String object.\nString str3 = new String(“Hello"); \nString str4 = new String(“Hello");\nJava String Methods\n•Java provides methods to work with Strings. \n•These methods manipulate and analyze text.\n•length()                                               \n•concat () \n•charAt ()\n•equals()\n•equalsIgnoreCase ()\n•indexOf ()\n•substring()\n•replace()\n•toLowerCase ()\n•toUpperCase ()\n•trim()\n•compareTo ()\n•valueOf ()•contains()\n•toCharArray ()\n•isEmpty ()\n•endsWith ()\n•1. Get String Length\nThe length() method returns the number of characters in a String.\n•2. Concatenate Strings\nYou can join two or more Strings. Use the + operator or the concat () method.\n•3. Access Characters\nUse the charAt () method to get a character at a specific index. Indexes start from 0.\n•4. Compare Strings\nThe equals() method compares two Strings. It checks if their content is the same. Use \nequalsIgnoreCase () to ignore case differences.\nDo not use == to compare String content. The == operator checks if two String references point \nto the same object in memory.\n•5. Find Substrings\nThe indexOf () method finds the first occurrence of a substring. It returns the index. If the \nsubstring is not found, it returns -1.\n•6. Extract Substrings\nThe substring() method extracts a portion of a String. You provide start and end indexes.\n•7. Replace Characters or Substrings\nUse replace() to replace characters or substrings.\n•8. Convert Case\nThe toLowerCase () and toUpperCase () methods change the case of a String.\n•9. Trim Whitespace\nThe trim() method removes leading and trailing whitespace.\nActivity\n1.\nString name = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (name.length ()); \n2.\nString s1 = "Hello";\nString s2 = "World";\nSystem.out.println (s1.concat(" " + s2)); \nSystem.out.println (s1 + " " + s2);       \n3.\nString text = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (text.charAt (2)); \n4.\nString a = "Hello";\nString b = "hello";\nSystem.out.println (a.equals (b));            \nSystem.out.println (a.equalsIgnoreCase (b));  \n5.\nString text = "banana";\nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("a"));  \nSystem.out.println (text.indexOf ("na")); \n6.\nString word = "Programming";\nSystem.out.println (word.substring (0, 4));\n7.\nString name = "car";\nSystem.out.println (name.replace ('c', 'b')); \n8.\nString word = "Java";\nSystem.out.println (word.toUpperCase ()); \nSystem.out.println (word.toLowerCase ()); \n9.\nString s = "  Hello Java  ";\nSystem.out.println (s.trim ()); \n10.\nString s1 = "apple";\nString s2 = "apple";\nSystem.out.println (s1.compareTo(s2));\nString name = "   Java Programming   ";\nSystem.out.println (name.trim ().substring(0, 4). toUpperCase ());\nString Immutability\nString str = "Java";\nstr.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); \nWhat will be the output? why?\n•Output: Java     //Not "Java Programming"\n•Because concat () creates a new String object, it doesn’t modify the original.\n•To store the new value, assign it back:\nString str = "Java";\nstr = str.concat (" Programming");\nSystem.out.println (str); // Output: Java Programming\n•Unlike other data types in Java, Strings are immutable. \n•It means that Strings are constant, their values cannot be changed after they are created.\n•New String is created whenever we do String manipulation. \n•The original String remains unchanged.\nThis immutability offers benefits:\n1. Thread Safety : Multiple threads can access a String without synchronization problems. One thread \ncannot change a String while another reads it.\n2. Security : Immutability is important for security. When you use Strings for sensitive data like \ndatabase credentials, their unchanging nature prevents unintended modifications.\n3. Performance : The String Pool relies on immutability. This helps save memory and improves \nperformance by reusing existing String objects.\nWhat will be the output?\nString s = “Colombo";\ns.concat (" City");\nSystem.out.println (s); \nStringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(“Colombo");\nsb.append (" City");\nSystem.out.println (sb); \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder\n•As String manipulations are resource consuming, Java provides two utility classes: StringBuffer  and \nStringBuilder.\n•StringBuffer  and StringBuilder are mutable classes . \nExample1:\nStringBuffer  sb = new StringBuffer ("Hello");\nsb.append (" World");\nSystem.out.println (sb); // Hello World\nExample2:\nStringBuilder sb2 = new StringBuilder("Java");\nsb2.append(" Rocks");\nSystem.out.println (sb2); // Java Rocks\nFind out the key difference between \nStringBuffer  and StringBuilder classes.\n \nStringBuffer StringBuilder\nOperations are thread -safe and synchronized Not thread -safe are not -synchronized\nUsed when multiple threads are working on the same \nString Used in a single -threaded environment\nPerformance is slower when compared to StringBuilder Performance is faster when compared to StringBuffer\nSyntax: StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Hello”); Syntax: StringBuilder var = new StringBuilder(“Hello”);\nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer  \nString vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer\n•The differences between String, StringBuffer , and StringBuilder are based on the following two \nparameters:\nMutability\nPerformance\nString StringBuffer StringBuilder\nString Pool Heap Heap\nImmutable Mutable Mutable\nNot used in a threaded \nenvironmentUsed in a multi -threaded environment Used in a single -threaded \nenvironment\nSlow Slower than StringBuilder but faster than \nStringFaster than StringBuffer\nString var =“Java”; \nString var=newString(“Java”); StringBuffer  var = new StringBuffer (“Java"); StringBuilder var = new \nStringBuilder(“Java");\nStrings with Special Characters\n•The backslash ( \\) escape character turns special characters into string characters\n•System.out.println ("She said, \\"Java is fun! \\"");\n•System.out.println ("Path: C: \\\\Program Files \\\\Java");Escape character Result Description\n\\' ' Single quote\n\\" " Double quote\n\\\\ \\ Backslash
261	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:09:34.820271	--- 9 - Exception Handling.pdf ---\nException \nHandling in Java\nLecture 9\n\nOutline\n•What is Exception in Java?\n•Exception Handling in Java\n•Why Use Exception Handling?\n•Exceptions Hierarchy\n•Errors Vs Exception\n•Types of Java Exceptions\n•Java Exception Keywords\n•throw Vs throws\nWhat is Exception in Java?\n•An exception is an event that occurs during the execution of a program that disrupts the normal \nflow of instructions. \n•Example:\nDividing a number by zero\nAccessing an invalid array index\nOpening a file that does not exist\nException Handling in Java\n•Exception Handling is a mechanism to handle runtime errors.\n•If an exception is not handled, it may lead to a system failure. That is why handling an exception is \nvery important.\n•Example Without Exception Handling:\n\n•Example With Exception Handling:\n\nWhy Use Exception Handling?\n•To maintain the normal flow of the program\n•To prevent program crashes\n•To handle errors more gracefully\nExceptions Hierarchy\n•All exception and error types are subclasses of class Throwable, which is the base class of hierarchy.\n•One branch is headed by Error which occurs at run -time and other by Exception that can happen \neither at compile time or run -time.\nErrors Vs Exception\nExceptions Errors\nPossible to recover Impossible to recover from an error\nExceptions can be either ‘checked’ or ‘unchecked’ Errors are of type ‘unchecked’\nCan occur at compile time or run time Occur at runtime\nTypes of Java Exceptions\n1. Checked Exceptions\nChecked exceptions are the exceptions that are checked at compile -time. \nThis means that the compiler verifies that the code handles these exceptions either by catching \nthem or declaring them in the method signature using the throws keyword.\n•2. Unchecked Exceptions (Runtime Exceptions)\nUnchecked exceptions, also known as runtime exceptions, are not checked at compile -time. \nThese exceptions usually occur due to programming errors, such as logic errors or incorrect \nassumptions in the code. \nThey do not need to be declared in the method signature using the throws keyword, making it \noptional to handle them.\nChecked Exceptions Examples:\n1. IOException : An exception is thrown when an input/output operation fails.\n\n2. SQLException : It is thrown when an error occurs while accessing a database.\n\n3. ClassNotFoundException : Occurs when trying to load a class that doesn’t exist in the classpath .\n\nUnchecked Exceptions Examples: \n1. ArithmeticException : It is thrown when an arithmetic operation fails, such as division by zero.\n\n2. NullPointerException : It is thrown when trying to access or call a method on an object reference \nthat is null.\n\n3. NumberFormatException : Occurs when you try to convert a non -numeric string into a number (like \ntrying to turn " abc" into an integer).\n\n4. ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException : It occurs when we try to access an array element with an \ninvalid index.\n\n5. StringIndexOutOfBoundsException : Occurs when you try to access a character position (index) in a \nstring that doesn’t exist.\n\nJava Exception Keywords\n•try: Contains code that may throw an exception\n•catch: Used to handle the exception\n•finally: Executes cleanup code (always runs)\n•throw: Used to explicitly throw an exception\n•throws: Declares exceptions that a method might throw\nThe try -catch Block\n•One of the primary mechanisms for handling exceptions in Java is the try -catch block. \n•The try block contains the code that may throw an exception, and the catch block is used to handle \nthe exception if it occurs. \ntry {  \n    // Code that may throw an exception       \n} catch ( ExceptionType  e) {  \n    // Exception handling code  \n}\nExample:\ntry {\n    int num = 10 / 0;\n} catch ( ArithmeticException  e) {\n    System.out.println ("You cannot divide by zero!");\n}\nHandling Multiple Exceptions\n•You can handle multiple types of exceptions by providing multiple catch blocks, each catching a \ndifferent type of exception. \ntry {  \n    // Code that may throw an exception  \n} catch ( IOException  e) {  \n    // Handle IOException   \n} catch ( NumberFormatException  e) {  \n    // Handle NumberFormatException   \n} catch (Exception e) {  \n    // Handle any other exceptions  \n}\nExample:\ntry {\n    int[] arr = new int[3];\n    arr[5] = 10; // ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException\n    int num = Integer.parseInt ("abc"); // NumberFormatException\n} catch ( ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException  e) {\n    System.out.println ("Invalid array index!");\n} catch ( NumberFormatException  e) {\n    System.out.println ("Invalid number format!");\n} catch ( Exception e ) {\n    System.out.println ("Something went wrong!");\n}\nThe finally Block\n•The finally block executes whether or not an exception occurs.\n•Commonly used to close files, database connections, or release resources.\ntry {  \n    // Code that may throw an exception  \n} catch (Exception e) {  \n    // Exception handling code  \n} finally {  \n    // Cleanup code  \n}\nExample:\ntry {\n    System.out.println ("Inside try block");\n    int result = 10 / 0;\n} catch ( Exception e ) {\n    System.out.println ("Exception caught");\n} finally {\n    System.out.println ("Finally block always executes");\n}\nThe throw Keyword\n•The throw keyword is used to explicitly throw an exception.\npublic class ExampleThrow  {\n    static void checkAge (int age) {\n        if (age < 18) {\n            throw  new ArithmeticException ("Access denied - You must be 18 or older.");\n        } else {\n            System.out.println ("Access granted - You are old enough!");\n        }\n    }\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        checkAge (16);\n    }\n}\nThe throws Keyword\n•The throws keyword is used in method declarations to indicate that a method may throw one or \nmore exceptions.\nimport java.io.*;\nclass ExampleThrows  {\n    void readFile () throws  IOException  {\n        FileReader  fr = new FileReader ("test.txt"); // File might not exist\n    }\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        ExampleThrows  obj = new ExampleThrows ();\n        try {\n            obj.readFile ();\n        } catch ( IOException  e) {\n            System.out.println ("File not found!");\n        }\n    }\n}\nthrow Vs throws\nthrow throws\nUsed to explicitly throw an exception Used to declare an exception\nChecked exceptions cannot be propagated using throw \nonlyChecked exceptions can be propagated\nUsed within a method Used with a method signature\nCannot throw multiple exceptions Can declare multiple exceptions
262	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:12:54.80424	--- 10 - Threads.pdf ---\nThreads in Java\nLecture 10\n\nOutline\n•What is a Thread?\n•Why Multi -threading?\n•Creating Threads in Java\n•Controlling the Threads\n•Thread Life Cycle\n•Thread Priority\nWhat is a Thread?\n•A thread is a lightweight subprocess and the smallest unit of execution.\n•Has a single flow of control: start → process → end.\n•Java’s main() runs in the main thread (single -threaded by default).\n•Java supports multi -threading: multiple threads run concurrently for : \nbetter performance & responsiveness. \nEfficient resource utilization\nWhy Multi -threading?\n•Better resource utilization \n•Responsive UIs\n•Parallel processing\nHow?\nAlthough only one thread runs at a time  on a single core , the JVM  rapidly switches between threads , \ngiving the illusion  of simultaneous execution (time -slicing).\nThis switch is called thread context switching. \nCreating Threads in Java\n•A thread program is created in the one of the following ways:\n1. Extend the "Thread“ class\n2. Implement the "Runnable“ interface\nExtending the Thread class\n•When extending the class Thread, the steps to be included:\n1. Extending the base class "Thread“\n2. Override the method "run" (All the thread program codes should include the run method)\n3. Create an instance for your class\n4. Call the method start() to instantiate the thread program process\nFormat:\nclass MyThread  extends Thread {\n  public void run(){\n  //Thread code included here\n  }\n}\nclass MainThread {\n  public static void main(){\n  MyThread  obj1 = new MyThread ();\n  obj1.start();\n  }\n}\nActivity\n•Create thread classes ThreadA , ThreadB , ThreadC . Override the method run by printing the \nintegers from 1 to 5. Create objects for each class and execute the method run using the method \nstart.\nImplementing runnable interface\n•Steps to follow:\n1. Declare the class as implementing runnable interface\n2. Implement the method run\n3. Create an instance for the declared class\n4. Create a Thread class instance, that should instantiate by the already created instance\n5. Call the method start() by thread class instance\n•Format\nclass MyThread  implements Runnable {\n  public void run(){\n  // Thread code included here\n  }\n}\nclass MainThread {\n  public static void main(String args[]){\n  MyThread  obj1  = new MyThread ();\n  Thread  thobj  = new Thread( obj1 );\n  thobj.start ();\n  }\n}\nActivity\n•Create a thread implements Runnable interface and override the method run by printing integers \nfrom 1 to 10. Execute the run method.\nControlling the thread\n•Controlling the thread can be done in 2 ways:\n1. Stopping a thread\n2. Blocking a thread\nStopping a thread\n•To stop a thread from running further, we can call the stop()  from the Thread class.\n•This method cause the Dead or Destroy state.\n•A thread move into the dead state will not re -join in the process.\nBlocking a thread\n•A thread can be temporarily block from its running process.\n•This is called blocking a Thread.\n•This will cause a thread to move down to the blocked state.\n•This can be achieved by following methods:\nsleep()\nwait()\nsuspend()\nsleep()  - Block period is in milli seconds.\nOnce the time expires and the thread re-enters to the runnable and subsequently the running state.\nwait() - Block the thread until certain condition occur\nwaiting thread re-enter the runnable state by calling the notify() from Thread class.\nsuspend()  - Block the thread until some errors were correct.\nsuspended thread re-enters the runnable state by calling the resume() from Thread class.\nThread Life Cycle\n•Threads in Java go through several states:\n1. New - Thread is created but not started.\n2. Runnable - Ready to run and waiting for CPU time.\n3. Running - Currently executing.\n4. Blocked or Idle - Temporarily inactive.\n5. Dead or Destroyed - Finished execution or stopped.\nState Transition Diagram of a Thread\n\nNew state\n•When we create a thread object, the thread is born and said to be in the Newborn / New state.\n•Once the thread object is created it is not schedule for running. \n•At this state we can do one of the followings:\n1. Schedule the thread for running using the start()\n2. Kill the thread by calling stop()\nRunnable state\n•The thread is ready to perform the execution and is waiting for the availability of the process.\n•Means thread has joined the queue of threads that are waiting for execution.\n•If all threads have same priority, then they are given the time slots for the execution in first come \nfirst serve manner.\nRunning state\n•The processor has given its time  to a Thread for the execution.\n•The running Thread will continue the execution until it complete its task.\n•Once the task completed then move to the death state.\n•Running thread may relinquishes its own control to another thread by its own, by calling the yield() \nmethod.\n•If the control is given to another thread, then the running thread goes back to the runnable state and \nthe subsequently enters to the running state.\n•Running can be block by the user, using thread blocking methods. Then running thread temporarily \nmoves to the block state.\nBlocked or Idle state\n•Threads are idle at this state. \n•Threads will move back as an active thread , or it can sed to the dead state by calling the \nappropriate thread method.\nDead or Destroyed state\n•Every thread has a life cycle. Once the life ends its automatically move to the dead state and never \nre enter the execution cycle.\n•Sometimes a thread will be sent to the dead state by calling stop() from any thread state.\n•stop() is the only method that can be called from any thread state.\nThread Priority\n•In java each thread is assigned a priority, which affects the execution order of the thread process.\n•The threads have the same priority will given the same treatment by scheduler and they work on \nfirst come first serve manner.\n•Java permits to set priority to a thread by calling the method setPriority ()\nEx:\nThreadobj.setPriority (int Number)\n•The parameter int Number is an integer parameter to set the priority. this can be one of the \nfollowing priority constants, or an integer from 1 -10.\n•MIN_PRIORITY = 1 (Lowest priority)\n•NORM -PRIORITY = 5 (Default priority)\n•MAX_PRIORITY = 10 (Highest priority)
263	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:27:38.353803	--- 5 - Core concepts of OOP.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 5\n\nThe four core concepts OOP\n•Encapsulation\n•Inheritance\n•Polymorphism\n•Abstraction\nEncapsulation\n•Encapsulation is a mechanism where you bind your data and code together as a single unit. \n•It also means to hide your data to make it safe from any modification. \n•Can achieve data hiding and controlled access.\n•The best way to understand encapsulation is to look at the example of a medical capsule , where \nthe drug is always safe inside the capsule. \n•Similarly, through encapsulation the methods and variables of a class are well hidden and safe.\n\n•We can achieve encapsulation in Java by:\nDeclaring the variables of a class as private .\nProviding public setter and getter methods to modify and view the variables values.\nAdvantages\n•Data hiding : If there are no getters, we cannot see the data. \n•Immutability : If there are no setters, we can’t change the data it is called as immutability. \n•Data validation : We can only check the value by using setters. This is called as data validation \nInheritance\n•Inheritance is a mechanism in which one class acquires (inherits) the properties and behaviors \n(fields and methods) of another class.\n•Inheritance is the process of creating sub classes from the existing base class . The sub class able to \naccess most of the members(excluding private type members) from its base class and include its \nown members.\n•It promotes code reusability and helps establish a natural parent –child relationship between \nclasses.\n•A child inherits certain characteristics (like eye color, blood group) from parents. Similarly, in Java, \nthere are two classes:\n1. Parent class ( Super class or Base class)\n2. Child class (Sub class or Derived class )\n•A class which inherits the properties is known as Child Class whereas a class whose properties are \ninherited is known as Parent class.\n•Inheritance is further classified into 4 types:\nSingle Inheritance\nMultilevel Inheritance\nHierarchical Inheritance\nMultiple inheritance (Not supported by Java)\nSingle Inheritance\n•In single inheritance, one class inherits the properties and behavior of another. \n•It enables a derived class to inherit the properties and behavior from a single parent class.\n•Let’s see the syntax for single inheritance:\nclass A\n{\n}\nclass B extends A {\n}\nMultilevel Inheritance\n•Having more than one parent class but at different levels , such type of inheritance is called \nMultilevel Inheritance.\n•Let’s see the syntax for multilevel inheritance in Java:\nclass A{\n}\nclass B extends A{\n}\nclass C extends B{\n}\nHierarchical Inheritance\n•When a class has more than one child classes (sub classes), then such kind of inheritance is known as \nhierarchical inheritance.\n•Let’s see the syntax for hierarchical inheritance in Java:\nclass A{\n}\nclass B extends A{\n}\nclass C extends A{\n}\nSingle, Multilevel, and Hierarchical    \nInheritances\n•The Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical Inheritances maintain " is a" relationship between the base class \nand the sub class.\n•This relation enable a subclass to legally access the members from its base class.\n•The term " is a" refers to " extends " keyword in Java.\n•"extends" keyword creates a legal relation between base and sub class.\n•That's why Java accepts Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical Inheritances.\nMultiple inheritance\n•Multiple inheritance is not supported by Java as it because it can lead to ambiguity problems (e.g., \nthe diamond problem).\n•This type of inheritance can only be achieved by the interfaces .\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism means taking many forms , where ‘poly’ means many and ‘morph’ means forms . \n•It is the ability of a variable, function or object to take on multiple forms. \n•In other words, polymorphism allows you define one interface or method and have multiple \nimplementations.\nLet’s consider this real -world scenario of \nmusical instruments!\n•Weknow that there aredifferent types ofinstruments such as\nGuitar, Piano, and Drum .Imagine there isaparent class called\nInstrument, and ithas three child classes :Guitar, Piano, and\nDrum .The parent class contains amethod playSound (),which is\ninherited byallchild classes .Now, asweallknow, aGuitar\nproduces sound differently compared toaPiano oraDrum .The\nGuitar willstrum strings, thePiano willplay keys, and theDrum\nwill create beats .Although allthree classes inherit the same\nmethod name playSound (),their implementation iscompletely\ndifferent depending onthetype ofinstrument .\n•The point ofthis discussion isthat asingle method name can\ntake multiple forms .The same method (playSound ())behaves\ndifferently depending onwhich object calls it.\nPolymorphism\n•Polymorphism in Java is of two types:\nCompile time polymorphism\nRun time polymorphism\nCompile time polymorphism\n•Compile -time polymorphism happens when multiple methods in the same class share the same \nname but differ in their parameter list (number of parameters or type of parameters).\n•The decision of which method to call is made by the compiler at compile time, not at runtime.\nRun time polymorphism\n•Runtime polymorphism happens when a subclass provides its own implementation of a method \nthat is already defined in its superclass.\n•Which version of the method gets executed is determined at runtime based on the object being \nreferred to, not the reference type.\nAbstraction\n•Abstraction is the process of hiding the internal implementation details and showing only the \nessential features to the user.\n•You can achieve abstraction in two ways:\nAbstract Class\nInterface\nSummary \n✓Encapsulation → Bundling data (attributes) and methods together\n✓Inheritance → Child class inherits properties & behaviors from parent class; promotes code reuse.\nTypes: Single, Multilevel, Hierarchical (Multiple via interfaces only).\n✓Polymorphism → One name, many forms.\nCompile -time → Method Overloading.\nRuntime → Method Overriding.\n✓Abstraction → Hiding internal details, showing only essential features.\nAchieved using abstract classes and interfaces.\n✓Real -world examples:\nEncapsulation → Medical capsule.\nInheritance → Child inherits eye color from parents.\nPolymorphism → Different instruments playing sound differently.
264	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:30:47.736285	--- 10 - Threads.pdf ---\nThreads in Java\nLecture 10\n\nOutline\n•What is a Thread?\n•Why Multi -threading?\n•Creating Threads in Java\n•Controlling the Threads\n•Thread Life Cycle\n•Thread Priority\nWhat is a Thread?\n•A thread is a lightweight subprocess and the smallest unit of execution.\n•Has a single flow of control: start → process → end.\n•Java’s main() runs in the main thread (single -threaded by default).\n•Java supports multi -threading: multiple threads run concurrently for : \nbetter performance & responsiveness. \nEfficient resource utilization\nWhy Multi -threading?\n•Better resource utilization \n•Responsive UIs\n•Parallel processing\nHow?\nAlthough only one thread runs at a time  on a single core , the JVM  rapidly switches between threads , \ngiving the illusion  of simultaneous execution (time -slicing).\nThis switch is called thread context switching. \nCreating Threads in Java\n•A thread program is created in the one of the following ways:\n1. Extend the "Thread“ class\n2. Implement the "Runnable“ interface\nExtending the Thread class\n•When extending the class Thread, the steps to be included:\n1. Extending the base class "Thread“\n2. Override the method "run" (All the thread program codes should include the run method)\n3. Create an instance for your class\n4. Call the method start() to instantiate the thread program process\nFormat:\nclass MyThread  extends Thread {\n  public void run(){\n  //Thread code included here\n  }\n}\nclass MainThread {\n  public static void main(){\n  MyThread  obj1 = new MyThread ();\n  obj1.start();\n  }\n}\nActivity\n•Create thread classes ThreadA , ThreadB , ThreadC . Override the method run by printing the \nintegers from 1 to 5. Create objects for each class and execute the method run using the method \nstart.\nImplementing runnable interface\n•Steps to follow:\n1. Declare the class as implementing runnable interface\n2. Implement the method run\n3. Create an instance for the declared class\n4. Create a Thread class instance, that should instantiate by the already created instance\n5. Call the method start() by thread class instance\n•Format\nclass MyThread  implements Runnable {\n  public void run(){\n  // Thread code included here\n  }\n}\nclass MainThread {\n  public static void main(String args[]){\n  MyThread  obj1  = new MyThread ();\n  Thread  thobj  = new Thread( obj1 );\n  thobj.start ();\n  }\n}\nActivity\n•Create a thread implements Runnable interface and override the method run by printing integers \nfrom 1 to 10. Execute the run method.\nControlling the thread\n•Controlling the thread can be done in 2 ways:\n1. Stopping a thread\n2. Blocking a thread\nStopping a thread\n•To stop a thread from running further, we can call the stop()  from the Thread class.\n•This method cause the Dead or Destroy state.\n•A thread move into the dead state will not re -join in the process.\nBlocking a thread\n•A thread can be temporarily block from its running process.\n•This is called blocking a Thread.\n•This will cause a thread to move down to the blocked state.\n•This can be achieved by following methods:\nsleep()\nwait()\nsuspend()\nsleep()  - Block period is in milli seconds.\nOnce the time expires and the thread re-enters to the runnable and subsequently the running state.\nwait() - Block the thread until certain condition occur\nwaiting thread re-enter the runnable state by calling the notify() from Thread class.\nsuspend()  - Block the thread until some errors were correct.\nsuspended thread re-enters the runnable state by calling the resume() from Thread class.\nThread Life Cycle\n•Threads in Java go through several states:\n1. New - Thread is created but not started.\n2. Runnable - Ready to run and waiting for CPU time.\n3. Running - Currently executing.\n4. Blocked or Idle - Temporarily inactive.\n5. Dead or Destroyed - Finished execution or stopped.\nState Transition Diagram of a Thread\n\nNew state\n•When we create a thread object, the thread is born and said to be in the Newborn / New state.\n•Once the thread object is created it is not schedule for running. \n•At this state we can do one of the followings:\n1. Schedule the thread for running using the start()\n2. Kill the thread by calling stop()\nRunnable state\n•The thread is ready to perform the execution and is waiting for the availability of the process.\n•Means thread has joined the queue of threads that are waiting for execution.\n•If all threads have same priority, then they are given the time slots for the execution in first come \nfirst serve manner.\nRunning state\n•The processor has given its time  to a Thread for the execution.\n•The running Thread will continue the execution until it complete its task.\n•Once the task completed then move to the death state.\n•Running thread may relinquishes its own control to another thread by its own, by calling the yield() \nmethod.\n•If the control is given to another thread, then the running thread goes back to the runnable state and \nthe subsequently enters to the running state.\n•Running can be block by the user, using thread blocking methods. Then running thread temporarily \nmoves to the block state.\nBlocked or Idle state\n•Threads are idle at this state. \n•Threads will move back as an active thread , or it can sed to the dead state by calling the \nappropriate thread method.\nDead or Destroyed state\n•Every thread has a life cycle. Once the life ends its automatically move to the dead state and never \nre enter the execution cycle.\n•Sometimes a thread will be sent to the dead state by calling stop() from any thread state.\n•stop() is the only method that can be called from any thread state.\nThread Priority\n•In java each thread is assigned a priority, which affects the execution order of the thread process.\n•The threads have the same priority will given the same treatment by scheduler and they work on \nfirst come first serve manner.\n•Java permits to set priority to a thread by calling the method setPriority ()\nEx:\nThreadobj.setPriority (int Number)\n•The parameter int Number is an integer parameter to set the priority. this can be one of the \nfollowing priority constants, or an integer from 1 -10.\n•MIN_PRIORITY = 1 (Lowest priority)\n•NORM -PRIORITY = 5 (Default priority)\n•MAX_PRIORITY = 10 (Highest priority)
265	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:32:12.790279	--- 6 - Interfaces.pdf ---\nFundamentals of \nobject -oriented programming\nLecture 6\nOutline\n•Interface\n•Why Interfaces are Important?\n•Multiple Interfaces\n•Multiple Inheritance in Java Using Interface\n•Newer Features for Interfaces (Java 8 and Later)\n•Difference Between Class and Interface\n•Abstract class\n•"final" Keyword in Java\n•Final class\n•Wrapper class\n•Autoboxing & Unboxing in Java\nWhat you know?\n•Data abstraction is the process of hiding certain details and showing only essential information to \nthe user.\n•Abstraction can be achieved with either abstract classes or interfaces.\nInterface\n•An interface in Java is a blueprint of a behavior . \n•Contains static constants and abstract methods.\n•To declare an interface, use the interface keyword. \n•To implement the interface, use the implements keyword.\n•An interface cannot contain a constructor (as it cannot be used to create objects)\n•Format:\ninterface < interface_name >{\n<final_variables >\n<abstract_methods >\n}\n•Key Properties of Interface:\nBy default, variables in an interface are public, static and final .\nIt is used to achieve abstraction and multiple inheritance in Java.\nWhy Interfaces are Important?\n•Make Code Abstract: You only see what methods are available. This makes your code simpler to use \nbecause you do not need to know the inner workings.\n•Allow Multiple Behaviors: Interfaces let a single class act like it has many kinds of behaviors. This is \na very powerful way to design your programs.\n•Help with Loose Connections: This means that classes depend on the rules defined by interfaces, \nnot on specific ways things are built. \nMultiple Interfaces\n•To implement multiple interfaces, separate them with a comma.\n•Note: A class can extend another class and similarly, an interface can extend another interface. \nHowever, only a class can implement an interface and the reverse (an interface implementing a \nclass) is not allowed.\nMultiple Inheritance in Java Using \nInterface\n•Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes to avoid ambiguity, but it supports multiple \ninheritance using interfaces.\n\nNewer Features for Interfaces (Java 8 \nand Later)\n•Java versions 8 and newer added new features to interfaces. These changes make interfaces more \npowerful for developers. They help you reuse code and write less repeated code.\nDefault Methods\nStatic Methods\nPrivate Methods (Java 9 and later)\nFind out the key difference between class \nand interface.\nDifference Between Class and Interface\nClass Interface\nCan create an object In an interface, you can't create an object\nSupports both instance and static variables Only supports public static final variables\nIt doesn't support multiple inheritance Supports multiple inheritance\nCan have constructors No constructors allowed\nDefined using class keyword Defined using interface keyword\nAbstract class\n•Restricted class that cannot be used to create objects.\n•We define the class using abstract keyword .\n•An abstract class can have both abstract and non abstract methods.\n•Rules for Java Abstract class\nAn abstract class must be declared using the abstract keyword.\nAbstract classes can include abstract and non -abstract methods.\nAn Abstract Class cannot be instantiated.\nThey can include constructors.\nCan includes static methods and final methods.\nAbstract Classes Vs Interfaces\nAbstract Classes Vs Interfaces\nAbstract Classes Interfaces\nCannot be directly created as an object and can \ncontain abstract methodsA blueprint for a class that contains only abstract \nmethods (before Java 8) and constant variables\nCan have methods with code and methods without \ncodeCan only have methods without code (before Java 8), \nAfter Java 8, can also have methods with default code, \nstatic methods, and private methods\nCan have special methods to create objects \n(constructors)Cannot have special methods to create objects \n(constructors).\nA class can only extend one abstract class A class can implement many interfaces\nMethods and variables can have different access levels, \nlike public, private, protectedMethods and variables are always public\nAbstract class is for “is -a” relationship with shared code Interface is for defining capabilities/behaviors (like \n“can -do” contract)\n"final" Keyword in Java\n•The final keyword in Java is a non-access modifier used to prevent modification. \n•It can be applied to variables (value cannot change), methods (cannot be overridden) and classes \n(cannot be extended).\nFinal variable ----> To create constant variable\nFinal method ---> Prevent method overriding\nFinal class ---> Prevent inheritance\nFinal class\n•When a class is declared with the final keyword in Java, it is called a final class. A final class cannot \nbe extended(inherited). \n•All wrapper classes in Java are final classes, such as String, Integer, etc. Any subclass cannot inherit \nfinal class\n•There are two uses of a final class: \nTo prevent inheritance , as final classes cannot be extended.\nTo create an immutable class\n•Advantage of the Final Class\nThe Final class provides security as it cannot be extended or inherited by any other class. Classes \nthat can be extended can leak potential users' sensitive data, but final classes make data \nelements safe and secure.\nThe final class is complete and immutable, so external access does not change data elements .\nWrapper class\n•Wrapper class provides a mechanism to convert primitive data types into wrapper class objects.\n•Following are the equivalent wrapper class objects of primitive data types.\n•Primitive Data Type          Wrapper Class\nbyte Byte\nshort Short\nint Integer\nlong Long\nfloat Float\ndouble Double\nboolean Boolean\nchar Character\n•To create a wrapper object, use the wrapper class.\nAutoboxing and Unboxing in Java\n•Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive data type into its corresponding wrapper \nclass object.\n•Introduced in Java 5 to simplify coding.\n•Unboxing is the reverse process: converting a wrapper class object back into its primitive type.\nActivity\n•1. Which of the following statements about abstract classes in Java is true?\na) Abstract classes cannot have any methods with implementations.\nb) Abstract classes cannot be instantiated.\nc) Abstract classes can only contain abstract methods.\nd) Abstract classes cannot have constructors.\n•2. Can an abstract class have static methods in Java?\na) Yes, but they cannot be called.\nb) No, static methods are not allowed in abstract classes.\nc) Yes, and they can be called without creating an instance of the class.\nd) No, because static methods must have a body.\n•3. Which keyword is used to declare a class as abstract in Java?\na) abstract\nb) Abstract\nc) final\nd) static\n•4. In Java, can an abstract class implement an interface without providing implementations for all \nits methods?\na) Yes, the abstract class can leave the implementation to its subclasses.\nb) No, it must provide implementations for all interface methods.\nc) Yes, but only if the interface has default methods.\nd) No, abstract classes cannot implement interfaces.\n•5. What is the outcome if a final method is attempted to be overridden in a subclass?\na) The code will compile, but the superclass method will be executed.\nb) The code will compile, and the subclass method will be executed.\nc) The code will result in a compilation error.\nd) The code will compile but will throw an exception at runtime.\n•6. What will happen if you try to change the value of a final variable after it has been initialized?   \npublic class Test {  \npublic static void main(String[] args) {  \nfinal int x = 10;  \nx = 20;  \n}  \n}    \na) Value will change to 20\nb) Compilation error\nc) Runtime error\nd) The program will run but the value will remain 10\n•7. Which of the following statements about the final keyword is true?\na) A final class can be subclassed.\nb) A final method can be overridden.\nc) A final variable must be initialized when declared.\nd) A final variable can be assigned a value only once.\n•8. Which of the following is a valid way to create an Integer object with the value 10?\nInteger val= new Integer(10);\nInteger val= Integer.valueOf (10);\nInteger val= 10;\nint val= 10;\n•9. What is the purpose of autoboxing in Java?\nConverting an object to its corresponding primitive data type.\nConverting a primitive data type to its corresponding object.\nConverting between different types of wrapper classes.\nConverting a string to its numeric equivalent.\nSummary \n✓Interface\nBlueprint of behavior → contains abstract methods & constants\nUsed for abstraction and multiple inheritance\n✓Why Interfaces are Important?\nMake code abstract → hide details\nAllow multiple behaviors (multiple inheritance)\nHelp with loose coupling between classes\n✓Abstract Class\nDeclared with abstract keyword\nCan have abstract and non -abstract methods\nCan include constructors\nCannot be instantiated\nSummary \n✓Final Keyword\nFinal variable → constant (value cannot change)\nFinal method → cannot be overridden\nFinal class → cannot be inherited\n✓Wrapper Classes\nConvert primitives → objects (e.g., int → Integer)\nNeeded for collections like ArrayList\nAll wrapper classes are final\n✓Autoboxing & Unboxing\nAutoboxing: primitive → wrapper object (automatic)\nUnboxing: wrapper object → primitive (automatic)
266	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:38:57.075146	--- 2 -  Variables and Loops.pdf ---\nIntroduction to Java \nProgramming\nLecture 2\n\nJava Syntax\n•Every line of code that runs in Java must be inside a class.\n•Class name should always start with an uppercase.\n\nThe main Method\n•public static void main(String[] args )\n•Every Java program execution starts with the main method.\n•A mandatory part of every Java program\nPrinting statement\n•System.out.println ("Welcome to Java!");\n•We use the println () method to print a line of text to the screen.\nSystem ---> built -in Java class \nout ---> object\nprintln () ---> method to print a line of text\nJava comments\n•Comments can be used to explain Java code, and to make it more readable.\n•The compiler does not compile the comments.\n•Java comments are of two types : \nSingle line comment\nMulti line comment\nDocumentation comments\nJava comments\n•Single -line comment\n// This is a single line comment\n•Multi -line comment\n/* The is a multi line comment\nused to add comment on multiple lines. */\n•Documentation comments\n/** \n*This is a \n*Documentation comment, used for\n*Documentation of the source code \n*/\nJava Variables\n•Variables are containers for storing data.\n•The general rules for naming variables are:\nCan contain letters, digits, underscores, and dollar signs\nMust begin with a letter, $ or _\nShould start with a lowercase letter, and cannot contain whitespace\nCannot use reserved words (such as int or boolean )\nNames are case -sensitive (" myNum " and " mynum " are different variables)\nDeclaring Variables\n•Syntax:\n<data_type > <variableName > = <value>;\n•Example\nString name = "Leena";\nint age = 27;\nDeclaring Variables\n•You can also declare a variable without assigning the value, and assign the value later:\nint age;\nage = 27;\nSystem.out.println (age);//27\n•Updating values:\nIf you assign a new value to an existing variable, it will overwrite the previous value\nage=28;\nSystem.out.println (age);//28\nMultiple variables in one line\n•To declare more than one variable of the same type, you can use a comma -separated list:\n•Instead of writing:\nint a = 2;\nint b = 9;\nint c = 5;\n•You can simply write:\nint a = 2, b = 9, c = 5;\nFinal keyword\n•When you do not want a variable's value to change, use the final keyword.\n•A variable declared with final becomes a constant, which means unchangeable and read -only:\nfinal int myNum = 7;\nmyNum = 8;  // Error: cannot assign a value to final variable ' myNum '\nData Types\n•Data types are divided into two groups:\nPrimitive data types (built -in)\nNon -primitive data types (reference types)\n•Primitive data types -byte, short, int, long, float, double, boolean , char \n•Non -primitive data types –String, Array, Class, Interface, and Objects\nData Types\n\nActivity\n1. Write a Java statement to declare an integer variable named age and assign the value 20 to it.\n2. How do you declare a double variable named salary with the value 35000.50 in Java?\n3. Write a Java statement to declare a boolean variable named isStudent and assign it the value \ntrue.\n4. How would you declare a character variable named grade and assign the value 'A' in Java?\n5. Write a Java statement to declare a String variable named name with the value "Ram".\nFind out the difference between \nprimitive and non -primitive data types\nPrimitive and non -primitive data types\nPrimitive Non -primitive\nBasic, built -in data types Derived, complex data types\nStores actual value in the memory Stores reference to the object\nFixed Not fixed\nTypically stored in stack memory Reference is in stack, object is in heap memory\nStarts with lowercase letter Starts with uppercase letter\nOperators in Java\n•Java divides the operators into the following groups:\nArithmetic operators (+, -, *, /, %)\nAssignment operators (=, +=, -=, etc.)\nRelational / Comparison operators (==, !=, >, <)\nLogical operators (&&, ||, !)\nConcatenation operator (+ for Strings)\nOperators in Java\n•Arithmetic Operators -To perform common mathematical operations.\n•Assignment Operators -To assign values to variables.\n•Comparison Operators -To compare two values (or variables) and the return value of a comparison \nis either true or false. \n•Logical Operators -To determine the logic between variables or values.\nOperators in Java\n•Concatenation operator\nTo combine both text and a variable\nTo add a variable to another variable\nTo combine two strings, we use concatenation operator\n•Example 1\nString name = "Ananth";\nSystem.out.println ("Hello " + name);\n•Example 2\nString firstName = "John ";\nString lastName = "Doe";\nString fullName = firstName + lastName ;\nSystem.out.println (fullName ); //John Doe\nOperators in Java\n•For numeric values, the ‘+’ character works as a mathematical operator\nint x = 2;\nint y = 9;\nSystem.out.println (x + y); //11\nActivity\nQ1.What will be the output of the following code?\nint x = 10;\nint y = 3;\nSystem.out.println (x / y);\nSystem.out.println (x % y);\nQ2.What does the following print on the screen?\nint a = 5, b = 8;\nSystem.out.println (a > b);\nSystem.out.println (a != b);\nActivity\nQ3.What will be the output following Java code segment?\nboolean p = true, q = false;\nSystem.out.println (p && q);\nSystem.out.println (p || q);\nSystem.out.println (!p);\nQ4. What will be the value of variable `num` after the code runs?\nint num = 10;\nnum += 5;\nnum *= 2;\nSystem.out.println (num);\nActivity\nQ5. What will be the result of:\nint x = 5;\nSystem.out.println (x++);\nSystem.out.println (++x);\nControl structures in Java\n•The if Statement\nto specify a block of Java code to be executed if a condition is true.\n•The condition inside the if statement must result in a boolean value\nif (condition) {\n// code to be executed \n}\n\nControl structures in Java\n•The if else Statement\nwhen the condition is true if block will be executed, if condition is not true else block will be \nexecuted\nif (condition) {\n// code to be executed if the condition is true\n} else {\n// code to be executed if the condition is false\n}\n•Short -hand if else, which is known as the ternary operator\nvariable = (condition) ? expressionTrue :  expressionFalse ;\n\nControl structures in Java\nThe else if ladder\nIf we want to test more than one condition, \nwe use else if ladder.\nif (condition1) {\n// executed if condition1 is true\n} else if (condition2) {\n// executed if the condition1 is false and condition2 is true\n} else {\n// executed if the condition1 is false and condition2 is false\n}\n\nControl structures in Java\nSwitch Statements\nIt is an alternative to an if-else-if ladder\nswitch(expression) {\ncase x:\n// code block\nbreak;\ncase y:\n// code block\nbreak;\ndefault:\n// code block\n}\n\nControl structures in Java\nHow switch statements works?\n•The switch expression is evaluated once.\n•The result is compared with each case value.\n•If there is a match, the matching block of code runs.\n•The break statement stops the switch after the matching case has run.\n•The default statement runs if there is no match.\nLoops\nLoops can execute a block of code as long as a specified condition is reached.\nWhile Loop:\nloops through a block of code as long as a specified condition is true\nwhile (condition) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\n\nLoops\nDo/While Loop:\nThis loop will execute the code block once, before checking if the condition is true. Then it will \nrepeat the loop as long as the condition is true.\ndo {\n// code block to be executed\n}\nwhile (condition);\n\nLoops\nFor Loop:\nWhen you know exactly how many times you want to loop through a block of code, use the for \nloop\nfor (statement 1; statement 2; statement 3) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\nStatement 1 is executed (one time) before the execution of the code block.\nStatement 2 defines the condition for executing the code block.\nStatement 3 is executed (every time) after the code block has been executed.\n\nLoops\nFor-Each loop:\nused to loop through elements in an array\nfor (type variableName : arrayName ) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\n\nActivity\nQ1. Consider the following code snippet. What will be printed on the console?\nint x = 10;\nif (x > 5) {\nSystem.out.println ("A");\n}\nSystem.out.println ("B");\nQ2. Suppose the variable y is initialized as below, what will be the output?\nint y = 8;\nif (y % 2 == 0) {\nSystem.out.println ("Even");\n} else {\nSystem.out.println ("Odd");\n}\nActivity\nQ3. A student’s grade is determined by the following code:\nint marks = 75;\nif (marks >= 90) {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade A");\n} else if (marks >= 60) {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade B");\n} else {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade C");\n}\nWhat grade will be printed on the screen?\nActivity\nQ4. Consider the switch statement below\nint day = 3;\nswitch(day) {\ncase 1: System.out.println ("Monday"); break;\ncase 2: System.out.println ("Tuesday"); break;\ncase 3: System.out.println ("Wednesday"); break;\ndefault: System.out.println ("Other day");\n}\nWhat will be the output?\nActivity\nQ5. How many times will "Hello" be printed?\nfor (int i= 0; i< 5; i++) {\nSystem.out.println ("Hello");\n}\nSummary \n✓Java program structure → everything inside a class\n✓The main() method is the entry point of execution\n✓Printing output with System.out.println ()\n✓Comments: single -line (//) and multi -line (/*...*/)\n✓Variables: rules for naming, declaring, updating values\n✓final keyword → constants (unchangeable values)\n✓Data Types: Primitive (int, double, char, boolean , etc.) and Non -primitive (String, Arrays, Classes, \nObjects)\n✓Operators: Arithmetic, Assignment, Comparison, Logical, Concatenation\n✓Control structures: if, if -else, if -else-if, switch\n✓Loops: while, do -while, for, for -each
