uted (every time) after the code block has been executed.\n\nLoops\nFor-Each loop:\nused to loop through elements in an array\nfor (type variableName : arrayName ) {\n// code block to be executed\n}\n\nActivity\nQ1. Consider the following code snippet. What will be printed on the console?\nint x = 10;\nif (x > 5) {\nSystem.out.println ("A");\n}\nSystem.out.println ("B");\nQ2. Suppose the variable y is initialized as below, what will be the output?\nint y = 8;\nif (y % 2 == 0) {\nSystem.out.println ("Even");\n} else {\nSystem.out.println ("Odd");\n}\nActivity\nQ3. A student’s grade is determined by the following code:\nint marks = 75;\nif (marks >= 90) {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade A");\n} else if (marks >= 60) {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade B");\n} else {\nSystem.out.println ("Grade C");\n}\nWhat grade will be printed on the screen?\nActivity\nQ4. Consider the switch statement below\nint day = 3;\nswitch(day) {\ncase 1: System.out.println ("Monday"); break;\ncase 2: System.out.println ("Tuesday"); break;\ncase 3: System.out.println ("Wednesday"); break;\ndefault: System.out.println ("Other day");\n}\nWhat will be the output?\nActivity\nQ5. How many times will "Hello" be printed?\nfor (int i= 0; i< 5; i++) {\nSystem.out.println ("Hello");\n}\nSummary \n✓Java program structure → everything inside a class\n✓The main() method is the entry point of execution\n✓Printing output with System.out.println ()\n✓Comments: single -line (//) and multi -line (/*...*/)\n✓Variables: rules for naming, declaring, updating values\n✓final keyword → constants (unchangeable values)\n✓Data Types: Primitive (int, double, char, boolean , etc.) and Non -primitive (String, Arrays, Classes, \nObjects)\n✓Operators: Arithmetic, Assignment, Comparison, Logical, Concatenation\n✓Control structures: if, if -else, if -else-if, switch\n✓Loops: while, do -while, for, for -each
269	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-12 01:49:15.254663	--- 9 - Exception Handling.pdf ---\nException \nHandling in Java\nLecture 9\n\nOutline\n•What is Exception in Java?\n•Exception Handling in Java\n•Why Use Exception Handling?\n•Exceptions Hierarchy\n•Errors Vs Exception\n•Types of Java Exceptions\n•Java Exception Keywords\n•throw Vs throws\nWhat is Exception in Java?\n•An exception is an event that occurs during the execution of a program that disrupts the normal \nflow of instructions. \n•Example:\nDividing a number by zero\nAccessing an invalid array index\nOpening a file that does not exist\nException Handling in Java\n•Exception Handling is a mechanism to handle runtime errors.\n•If an exception is not handled, it may lead to a system failure. That is why handling an exception is \nvery important.\n•Example Without Exception Handling:\n\n•Example With Exception Handling:\n\nWhy Use Exception Handling?\n•To maintain the normal flow of the program\n•To prevent program crashes\n•To handle errors more gracefully\nExceptions Hierarchy\n•All exception and error types are subclasses of class Throwable, which is the base class of hierarchy.\n•One branch is headed by Error which occurs at run -time and other by Exception that can happen \neither at compile time or run -time.\nErrors Vs Exception\nExceptions Errors\nPossible to recover Impossible to recover from an error\nExceptions can be either ‘checked’ or ‘unchecked’ Errors are of type ‘unchecked’\nCan occur at compile time or run time Occur at runtime\nTypes of Java Exceptions\n1. Checked Exceptions\nChecked exceptions are the exceptions that are checked at compile -time. \nThis means that the compiler verifies that the code handles these exceptions either by catching \nthem or declaring them in the method signature using the throws keyword.\n•2. Unchecked Exceptions (Runtime Exceptions)\nUnchecked exceptions, also known as runtime exceptions, are not checked at compile -time. \nThese exceptions usually occur due to programming errors, such as logic errors or incorrect \nassumptions in the code. \nThey do not need to be declared in the method signature using the throws keyword, making it \noptional to handle them.\nChecked Exceptions Examples:\n1. IOException : An exception is thrown when an input/output operation fails.\n\n2. SQLException : It is thrown when an error occurs while accessing a database.\n\n3. ClassNotFoundException : Occurs when trying to load a class that doesn’t exist in the classpath .\n\nUnchecked Exceptions Examples: \n1. ArithmeticException : It is thrown when an arithmetic operation fails, such as division by zero.\n\n2. NullPointerException : It is thrown when trying to access or call a method on an object reference \nthat is null.\n\n3. NumberFormatException : Occurs when you try to convert a non -numeric string into a number (like \ntrying to turn " abc" into an integer).\n\n4. ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException : It occurs when we try to access an array element with an \ninvalid index.\n\n5. StringIndexOutOfBoundsException : Occurs when you try to access a character position (index) in a \nstring that doesn’t exist.\n\nJava Exception Keywords\n•try: Contains code that may throw an exception\n•catch: Used to handle the exception\n•finally: Executes cleanup code (always runs)\n•throw: Used to explicitly throw an exception\n•throws: Declares exceptions that a method might throw\nThe try -catch Block\n•One of the primary mechanisms for handling exceptions in Java is the try -catch block. \n•The try block contains the code that may throw an exception, and the catch block is used to handle \nthe exception if it occurs. \ntry {  \n    // Code that may throw an exception       \n} catch ( ExceptionType  e) {  \n    // Exception handling code  \n}\nExample:\ntry {\n    int num = 10 / 0;\n} catch ( ArithmeticException  e) {\n    System.out.println ("You cannot divide by zero!");\n}\nHandling Multiple Exceptions\n•You can handle multiple types of exceptions by providing multiple catch blocks, each catching a \ndifferent type of exception. \ntry {  \n    // Code that may throw an exception  \n} catch ( IOException  e) {  \n    // Handle IOException   \n} catch ( NumberFormatException  e) {  \n    // Handle NumberFormatException   \n} catch (Exception e) {  \n    // Handle any other exceptions  \n}\nExample:\ntry {\n    int[] arr = new int[3];\n    arr[5] = 10; // ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException\n    int num = Integer.parseInt ("abc"); // NumberFormatException\n} catch ( ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException  e) {\n    System.out.println ("Invalid array index!");\n} catch ( NumberFormatException  e) {\n    System.out.println ("Invalid number format!");\n} catch ( Exception e ) {\n    System.out.println ("Something went wrong!");\n}\nThe finally Block\n•The finally block executes whether or not an exception occurs.\n•Commonly used to close files, database connections, or release resources.\ntry {  \n    // Code that may throw an exception  \n} catch (Exception e) {  \n    // Exception handling code  \n} finally {  \n    // Cleanup code  \n}\nExample:\ntry {\n    System.out.println ("Inside try block");\n    int result = 10 / 0;\n} catch ( Exception e ) {\n    System.out.println ("Exception caught");\n} finally {\n    System.out.println ("Finally block always executes");\n}\nThe throw Keyword\n•The throw keyword is used to explicitly throw an exception.\npublic class ExampleThrow  {\n    static void checkAge (int age) {\n        if (age < 18) {\n            throw  new ArithmeticException ("Access denied - You must be 18 or older.");\n        } else {\n            System.out.println ("Access granted - You are old enough!");\n        }\n    }\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        checkAge (16);\n    }\n}\nThe throws Keyword\n•The throws keyword is used in method declarations to indicate that a method may throw one or \nmore exceptions.\nimport java.io.*;\nclass ExampleThrows  {\n    void readFile () throws  IOException  {\n        FileReader  fr = new FileReader ("test.txt"); // File might not exist\n    }\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        ExampleThrows  obj = new ExampleThrows ();\n        try {\n            obj.readFile ();\n        } catch ( IOException  e) {\n            System.out.println ("File not found!");\n        }\n    }\n}\nthrow Vs throws\nthrow throws\nUsed to explicitly throw an exception Used to declare an exception\nChecked exceptions cannot be propagated using throw \nonlyChecked exceptions can be propagated\nUsed within a method Used with a method signature\nCannot throw multiple exceptions Can declare multiple exceptions
286	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-13 17:30:30.71002	--- 8 - Dietary guidelines.pdf ---\nFood based dietary guidelines \nand diet planning  \nDr. Thilanka Ranathunga\nFundamentals of Human Nutrition \n\nLearning objectives \n•Identify the Sri Lankan dietary guidelines \n•Plan a healthy diet using dietary guidelines for \ndifferent stages of life \nFood based dietary guidelines \n(FBDG) definition  \n•Science -based recommendations in the form of \nguidelines for healthy eating. \n•For consumer information\n•Appropriate for the region or country\n•Each country should have FBDGs\n•Culturally acceptable and practical to implement\nFBDG for Sri Lankans \n1.Add colour to your daily meals, balancing the \ncorrect amounts\n-Incorporate following food groups \na.Cereals and starchy foods \nb.Fruits\nc.Vegetables and green leaves\nd.Fish/meat/eggs/pulses\ne.Milk and milk products \nf.Nuts, oil and oily seeds \n\n2. Eat whole grains instead of refined \n-Less wheat flour preparations\n-Identify the serving sizes \n\n3. Eat two vegetables one leafy green vegetable \nand two fruits daily \n•Eat underutilized fruits and vegetables too\n\n4. Add fish, eggs or lean meat together with pulses in \neach meal \n-Reduce the consumption of red meat (ex –beef, \npork)\n-Remove skin part in chicken\n-Vegetarians : consume more pulses  \n\n5. Consume fresh milk or fermented milk \nproducts\n\n6. Eat handful of nuts, oily seeds and oil dail y\n(ex –avocado, peanut, sesame) \nAdditional guidelines\n•Limit : deep fried foods, red meat, butter\n•Limit trans fats : deep fried foods, margarine, \nprocessed foods\n•Don’t use oil repeatedly : will form trans fat\n\n7. Limit salt intake & use iodized salt\n-5 g per day (2300 mg of Na) \n\n8. Eat less sugar and sweet foods\n•Those are empty calorie foods \n•Risk for diabetes \n\n9. Drink 8 –10 glasses of water\n\n10.Be physically activitive\n\nServing sizes and types of foods for \neach stage of life \nPregnancy \n\nServing sizes and types of foods for \neach stage of life \nChild less than 6 months : Breast milk  \n\n•6 –12 months of age \n\nChildren for 6 –10 years \n•Children and adolescents
287	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 10 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	10	30	easy	2026-04-13 17:35:12.939781	--- 1 - FHN concepts and food groups.pdf ---\nFundamentals of Human \nNutrition \nDr. Thilanka Ranathunga\nSenior Lecturer, Dept. of Nutrition and Dietetics, \nWUSL \n1\n2\n\nClasses of Nutrients and Concepts \nof Human Nutrition \n3\nAims\n•To provide students with understanding of general \nprinciples of human nutrition with,\n-different nutrients and its classifications\n-different food groups\n-nutritional value / health implications of each food \ngroup \n4\nLearning objectives \n•Define “nutrients” \n•List the different groups of nutrients and food \ngroups\n•State the health importance of each group of \nnutrients and food groups\n5\nWhat is nutrient? \n1.Nutrients are compounds in foods essential for human  \nhealth. \nIt provides,\n-energy\n-the building bloc ks for repair and growth of the body\n-substances necessary to regulate chemical processes \ninside the body\n2. A nutrient is a substance used by an organism to survive, \ngrow, and reproduce.\n6\nGroups of nutrients \nThere are five major nutrients\n•Carbohydrates (CHO)\n•Proteins\n•Fats\n•Vitamins\n•Minerals\nOther compounds \n•Dietary fibers\n•Bioactive compounds \n•Water Macro \nnutrients \nMicro nutrients \n7Non \nnutrients \n\nBroad categories of nutrients \n•Macro nutrients : Nutrients that a person needs in large \nquantities \n•Include protein, carbohydrates, and fats\n•Micro nutrients : Nutrients that a person needs in small \nquantities \n•Vitamins and minerals\n8\nMain food groups and its health \nimportance\n9\nMain food groups \n•There are 8 food groups\n1. Cereals and starchy roots \n2. Fruits\n3. Vegetables\n4. Meat, fish & poultry\n5. Pulses\n6. Milk & milk products\n7. Fats & oil\n8. Sugar & sweets\n\nCereals and starchy roots \n•Called as grains\n•Rice, wheat, rye, oats, barley, millet, maize\n•Nutritional composition\n-Mainly carbohydrates : starch \n-Provide energy (4 kcal per 1g)\n-B group vitamins  (unrefined varieties) \n-Dietary fiber (unrefined varieties) \nMillet\nWheat\nRye\nOats BarleyMaize\nCereals and starchy roots cont … \n•Starchy roots : plants which store edible starch in roots\n•Nutritional composition \n-Carbohydrates  \n-Protein 1 –2 %\n-Dietary fiber \n-Bioactive compounds  \n•Excess consumption can lead to obesity \n\nFruits \n•Sweet and fleshy product of a tree or other plant that \ncontains seed\n•Nutritional composition \n-Vitamins (Vit C, ßcarotene)\n-Bioactive compounds\n-Dietary fibers\n•Underutilized varieties are important\n•Better to consume large amounts\n\nVegetables\n•Any parts of plants usually their leaves, fruits, or \nseeds that can be consumed\n•Nutritional composition \n-Vitamins : B group, A \n-Dietary fibers \n-Minerals : Na, K, Ca, Mg\n-Bioactive compounds\n•Underutilized varieties are important\n\nMeat fish and paltry \n•Animal origin foods \n•Nutritional composition\n-High quality protein\n-Saturated fats : Specially in red meat (beef, lamb, \nmutton, pork)\n-Too much consumption leads to increased protein \nintake : bad for kidney\n\nPulses \n•Pulses are the edible seeds of plants in the legume family\n•Peas, Chickpeas, Cowpea, Kidney beans, Soya bean, Lentils\nBlack beans\n•Nutritional composition\n-Proteins source for vegetarians : Lysine  \n-Dietary fiber\n-Bioactive compounds \nToo much consumption : obesity\n\nMilk and milk products \n•Milk is a white liquid produced by the mammary glands \nof mammals\n•Yogurt, cheese, curd (fermented products : digestion \nand absorption is easy)\n•Nutritional composition\n-High quality proteins\n-Saturated fats : in full cream milk\n-Too much consumption of full cream milk increase the \nrisk of heart diseases \n\nFats and oil\n•Oil : any nonpolar chemical substance from plant or \nanimals, liquids in room temperature\n•Fats : Non polar compounds, solid at room \ntemperature, from animals or plants\n•Butter, margarine, coconut oil, sesame oil, safflower \noil, olive oil, palm oil, nuts (cashew, ground nuts, \nalmond) \n•Nutritional composition\n-Fatty acids (healthy and unhealthy) and glycerol\n\nFats and oil cont …\n•High calorie (9 kcal per 1g)\n•Too much consumption can increase the risk of \nNCDs and obesity \n\nSugar and sweets \n•Table sugar (sucrose), honey, gaggery, candies, jam, jelly, \nsyrups \n•Nutritional composition \n-Empty calorie (no other nutrients)\n-Too much intake increase the risk of diabetes and other \nNon communicable diseases (NCDs)\n-Added sugar recommendation;\n-Men : 36 g /day (9 tea spoons)\n-Women : 25 g/day  ( 6 tea spoons)
288	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 5 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	5	1	easy	2026-04-13 17:38:37.428114	--- 5 - Fat soluble vitamins.pdf ---\nFat soluble vitamins \nFundamentals of Human Nutrition \n1\nVitamin A – Introduction \n•Two groups of compounds have vitamin A activity: \n•Vitamin A  : Retinol, retinaldehyde, and retinoic acid (In \nanimal sources) \n•Provitamin A  : Carotenoids ( β-Carotene) (in plant \nsources) \n2\nFunctions \n•Involve in vision : normal function of retina and \nepithelial carfare of retina \n•Maintain health epithelial cell integrity : cell \ndifferentiation to produce goblet cells \n•Facilitate normal bone growth – maintain the \nfunctions of osteoblast and osteoclast cells \n•Act as antioxidant \n•Synthesis of immune cells \n•Involve in embryonic development and reproduction \n3\nVitamin A and vision \n•The form of Vitamin A in the visual cycle is retinal. \n•Within the eye, 11- cis-retinal is bound to protein \n"opsin" to form rhodospin in rods cells and iodopsin in \ncones cells \n•Rodopsin - vision at dark light \n•Iodopsin – vision at bright light \n•As light enters the eye, the - cis-retinal is converted all \n"trans retinal” (isomarization) \n•The all-"trans retinal dissociates” from the opsin called \nphoto-bleaching. \n4\n5\n6\n7\nSources of Vitamin A \n•Animal sources : meat, fish, liver, milk and milk \nproducts, eggs yolk \n•Plant sources \n•Vegetable oil, dark green & deep yellow F & V \n•Broccoli, spinach, carrots, pumpkin, sweet potatoes, \n•Mangoes, papaya \n8\nVitamin A deficiency \n•Poor vision : night blindness \n•Dry skin \n•Dry eye : Xerophthalmia, Keratomalacia, Bitot’s spot \n•Delay growth \n•Poor wound healing \n•Frequent infections \n•Deformed bones \n9\nBitot’s spot Keratomalacia : The surface of the \nconjunctiva (the membrane that lines \nthe eyelids and covers the white of \nthe eye) and cornea dries, sometimes \nleading to corneal ulcers and bacterial \ninfections and cloudy. The tear glands \nare also affected, resulting in an \ninadequate tear film and dry eyes. \n10\nVitamin D \n•Skin synthesis vitamin D in multi-step process \n•About 90% of vitamin D requirement is supplied by \ncutaneous synthesis \n•Two forms in the diet, \n- Cholecalciferol : D3 – animal sources \n- Ergocalciferol : D2 – plant sources \n11\n\nCutaneous vitamin D synthesis \nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=onSPZ0aBUKM&t=165s \n\nVitamin D Functions \n13\n\n14\n\n15\n\nVit D food Sources \n•Sunlight  - main source, 10 – 20 minutes sun \nexposure 3 - 4 times a day \n•Time vary depending on skin type, genetics \n•Mushrooms (sun grown) \n•Meat, liver, tuna, salmon, sardine, Egg yolk \n•Milk and milk products \n•Fortified foods – milk powder, butter, margarine \n16\n\nVitamin D Deficiency \n•Deficiency = lack of mineral for bone; weakened \nbones, bowed legs \n•Children = Rickets : impaired mineralization of bone \nmatrix in growing skeleton due to low calcium \nabsorption \n•Adults = Osteomalacia : demineralization \n17\n\nVitamin E \nFunctions \n•Antioxidant  - protecting cell membranes and \nplasma lipoproteins from free radical damage \n•Involve in gene expression \n•Neurological functions \n•Regulation of oxidation reduction reactions \n•Maintain cell membrane stability \n18\nSources of Vitamin E \n•Vegetable oils - Sunflower oil, palm oil \n•Nuts \n•Seeds \n•Whole grains \n•Wheat germ \n•Avocado \n•Toxicity and deficiencies are rare \n19\n\nVitamin E Deficiency \n•Ataxia  : lack of voluntary coordination of muscle \nmovements \n•Myopathy – wasting \n•Peripheral neuropathy - damage to nerves \n•Retinopathy \n•Impairment of the immune response \n20\n\nVitamin K \nFunctions \n•Involve in blood clotting \n•Involve in electron transport chain : energy \nproduction \n•Antioxidant \n•Improve bone density :facilitate osteoblast cell \nformation \n21\n22\n\nDeficiency \n•Excessive bleeding – bleeding in intestine, ENT \n(Ear, Norse and Throat) bleeding \n•Poor bone development \n23\n\nSources of Vitamin K \n•Cabbage \n•Mustard \n•Spinach \n•About 1/2 from intestinal bacteria : Vitamin K \ninjection is given at birth \n•Deficiency usually seen when disease or \nchronic antibiotic use \n•K is low in breast milk, therefore vitamin K is \ngiven as injections at birth \n24
289	1	\N	Easy Quiz - 5 Questions	AI-generated easy level quiz	5	30	easy	2026-04-18 14:39:31.806857	--- 2 - CPU Structure and ISA.pdf ---\n3/16/2026\n1CPU Structure and \nInstruction Set \nArchitecture\nIntroduction to Computer ArchitectureIntroduction to Computer Architecture\n● Computer architecture refers to the design and \norganization of a computer system's components \nand their interactions.\n● It encompasses both hardware and software \naspects, focusing on how these elements work \ntogether to execute instructions and process \ndata efficiently.\nComputer Architecture vs Computer Organization\n● Computer Architecture:\n○ Focuses on functional behavior visible to \nprogrammers\n○ Examples: data type sizes, instruction set\n● Computer Organization:\n○ Deals with structural relationships not visible \nto programmers\n○ Examples: clock frequency, physical memory sizeComputer Architecture vs Computer Organization\n● Computers have wide variety of types\n○ Single chip microcomputers\n○ Supercomputers\n● The variation is not only on cost but in size, performance \nand application\n● There are various definitions\n○ Computer Architecture: the attributes of the computer system that are \nvisible to programmers (i.e the attributes that have a direct impact on \nthe logical execution of a program)\n○ Computer Organization: the operational units and their interconnection \nthat realize the architectural specifications1 2\n3 4\n3/16/2026\n2Language of Instructions\n● Humans understand complex languages (e.g., English, \nJapanese)\n● Computers understand simple instructions (e.g., Add A,B; \nMul A,B)\n● Instruction Set Architecture (ISA): The complete set of \ninstructions a processor can execute\n● The semantics of all the instructions supported by a \nprocessor is known as its Instruction Set Architecture \n(ISA)Features of an Instruction Set Architecture (ISA)\n1. Complete: Able to implement all user-written programs\n2. Concise: Limited size, typically 32-1000 instructions\n3. Generic: Instructions should not be overly specialized\nEg: adds a number with 15 - instruction is too specialized\n4. Simple: Instructions should not be unnecessarily complicated\nDesigning an ISA: Key Considerations\n● Number of instructions\n● Functionality of instructions\n● Complexity level\n● Two main paradigms:\n○ RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Computer)\n○ CISC (Complex Instruction Set Computer)RISC vs CISC\nRISC:\n● Simple, regular instruction structure\n● Fewer instructions (64-128)\n● Example: ARM\nCISC:\n● Complex, irregular instructions\n● Multiple operands\n● Larger instruction set\n● Example: Intel x865 6\n7 8\n3/16/2026\n3Levels of machine\n Levels of Machine Architecture\n● User ISA level: Instructions visible to programmer\n● System ISA level: Privileged instructions for OS\n● Hardware level: Actual implementation of \ninstructions\nComputer Architect's Role\n● Design ISA for optimal programming utility and \nperformance\n● Design hardware for best instruction implementation\n● Use performance measurement tools (e.g.benchmarks)\n● Balance performance of CPU, memory, I/O devices, \nand interconnections\n● Meet performance goals at lowest costComputer Architect's Role\n● Computer architects must design a computer to \nmeet functional requirements as well as price, \npower, performance, and availability goals. \n● Different functional requirements \n○ Application area \n○ Level of software compatibility \n○ Operating system requirements9 10\n11 12\n3/16/2026\n4What is a "better" computer? What is the "best" computer?\n○One machine may perform well for a \nparticular aspect but not for another.\n○There is no such “better” or “best” \ncomputer, It depends on user’s requirements \nand cost.Computer  COST FACTORS:\n● Cost of hardware design \n● cost of software design (OS, \napplications) \n● cost of manufacture \n● cost to end purchaser\nComputer Performance Factors\n● Program characteristics (size, frequency of \nexecution)\n● Number of users and their expertise\n● I/O device requirements\n● Technological advancements (more transistors, \nfaster switching)\n● Innovative architectures and implementationsDefining Performance: Response Time\n● Response time: Time between start and completion of an \nevent\n● Execution time is the reciprocal of performance\n● Performance comparison: "X is n times faster than Y"\n13 14\n15 16\n3/16/2026\n5Performance Metrics\nFor users:\n● Response time: Elapsed time for program execution\nFor computer center managers:\n● Throughput: Number of jobs completed per unit timePerformance Metrics\n● Is throughput = 1/average response time? \n○ Only if NO overlap \n○ Otherwise, throughput > 1/av. response time \n○ E.g. car assembly factory \n■ 4 hours to produce a car (response time) \n■ 6 cars per an hour produced (throughput) \n■ In general there is no relationship between these 2 metrics \n■ Throughput of the factory may increase to 18 cars per an \nhour without changing time to produce one car. \n■ How?\nCPU Time: True Measure of Processor Performance\n● Time spent running a program \n● It doesn’t include the time waiting for I/O and \nrunning other programs \n● CPU time is a true measure of processor performance\nCycles Per Instruction (CPI)\n● All computers are constructed using a clock to operate its \ncircuits. \n● A “cycle” is technically a pulse synchronization by an \ninternal oscillator, but for our purpose, they are a basic \nunit that helps understand a CPU’s speed. During each cycle, \nbillions of transistors within the processor open and close. \n● The clock speed measures the number of cycles your CPU \nexecutes per second, measured in Hz (GHz, MHz)17 18\n19 20\n3/16/2026\n6CPU Time Formula\n Factors Affecting Processor Performance\n1. Clock cycle (clock rate)\n2. Cycles Per Instruction (CPI)\n3. Instruction Count (IC)\nAll three factors equally affect performance and are \ninterdependent.\nPerformance Improvement Considerations\n● Changing one factor often affects others\n○ Clock cycle: Influenced by hardware technology \nand organization\n○ CPI: Affected by organization and ISA\n○ IC: Impacted by ISA and compiler technologyPerformance Calculation Example\nProblem: \nA program takes 10s on a 400 MHz computer. We want it \nto run in 6s, but increasing clock rate will increase \ntotal clock cycles by 1.2 times.\nWhat's the minimum required clock rate?21 22\n23 24\n3/16/2026\n7Performance Calculation Solution\n Example\nOur program takes 10s to run on computer A, which has 400 \nMHz clock.We want it to run in 6s. The designer says that \nthe clock rate can be increased, but it will cause the \ntotal number of clock cycles for the program to increase \nto 1.2 times the previous value. \nWhat is the minimum clock rate required to get the \ndesired speedup ?\nExample\nOur program takes 10s to run on \ncomputer A, which has 400 MHz \nclock.We want it to run in 6s. \nThe designer says that the clock \nrate can be increased, but it \nwill cause the total number of \nclock cycles for the program to \nincrease to 1.2 times the \nprevious value. \nWhat is the minimum clock rate \nrequired to get the desired \nspeedup ?\nExample\nSuppose we have 2 implementations of the same instruction \nset architecture. \nComputer A has a clock cycle time of 10 nsec and a CPI of \n2.0 for some program, and computer B has a clock cycle time \nof 20 nsec and a CPI of 1.2 for the same program. \nWhich machine is faster for this program?25 26\n27 28\n3/16/2026\n8Key Takeaways\n● Computer architecture involves designing both \nhardware and software components\n● ISA is crucial in defining a computer's \ncapabilities\n● Performance measurement considers various factors \nlike response time and throughput\n● CPU time is a key metric for processor performance\n● Improving performance requires balancing multiple \ninterdependent factors\n29
